const a = [
  {"id":1812,"text":"While examining the lateral view of the X-ray of the skull, a radiologist points out a region that is the meeting point of the parietomastoid, occipitomastoid, and lambdoid sutures. What point is he referring to?","explanation":"The **asterion** is an anatomical landmark located at the junction of the parietomastoid, occipitomastoid, and lambdoid sutures. It is situated in the temporal region of the skull, typically at the level of the asterion.\r\n\r\nIdentifying the asterion is important for various clinical purposes, including neurosurgery, radiology, and anatomical localization. For example, it serves as a reference point for the placement of burr holes during surgical procedures and is also used in cranial measurements and radiographic interpretation.","reference":"Chung KW, Chung HM, Halliday NL. BRS: Gross Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer Health; 2015: 369.","responses":[{"text":"Asterion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lambda","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bregma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1945,"text":"The lymphatic drainage from the palatine tonsil drains into which of the following lymph nodes?","explanation":"The lymphatic drainage from the palatine tonsil primarily drains into the **jugulodigastric lymph nodes**.\r\n\r\nThe palatine tonsil is a paired lymphoid structure located at the back of the throat, between the palatoglossal and palatopharyngeal arches. It is an important component of the immune system and helps defend against infections. The lymphatic vessels from the palatine tonsil carry lymphatic fluid, which contains immune cells and debris, to nearby lymph nodes for filtration and immune response.\r\n\r\nThe jugulodigastric lymph nodes, also known as the deep cervical lymph nodes, are located along the internal jugular vein in the neck. These nodes receive lymphatic drainage from various structures in the head and neck region, including the palatine tonsil. Therefore, when the palatine tonsil is involved in an infection or inflammation, the lymphatic drainage from the tonsil will pass through the jugulodigastric nodes.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1039.","responses":[{"text":"Superficial cervical","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep cervical","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submental","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jugulodigastric","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1954,"text":"The auditory ossicles articulate through which kind of joint?","explanation":"The auditory ossicles, which are a group of three small bones in the middle ear (malleus, incus, and stapes), articulate through a **synovial joint**. \r\n\r\nSynovial joints are characterized by the presence of a synovial cavity filled with synovial fluid, which lubricates the joint and allows for smooth movement. These joints are also surrounded by a joint capsule composed of fibrous connective tissue.\r\n\r\nThe articulation between the auditory ossicles provides flexibility and allows for the transmission of sound vibrations from the tympanic membrane to the inner ear. The synovial joint allows for precise and coordinated movements of the ossicles, contributing to the overall function of the auditory system.","reference":"Gaillard F. Middle ear ossicles | radiology reference article | radiopaedia. Org. Radiopaedia. https://radiopaedia.org/articles/middle-ear-ossicles","responses":[{"text":"Fibrocartilaginous joint","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Synovial joint","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrous joint","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cartilaginous joint","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Syndesmoses","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1955,"text":"Which of the following branches of the maxillary artery passes through the foramen spinosum?","explanation":"The branch of the maxillary artery that passes through the **foramen spinosum** is the **middle meningeal artery**.\r\n\r\nThe middle meningeal artery is an important branch of the maxillary artery that supplies the meninges, bones, and other structures in the cranial cavity. It enters the cranial cavity through the foramen spinosum, which is located in the greater wing of the sphenoid bone. Once inside the cranial cavity, the middle meningeal artery runs in the epidural space between the dura mater and the inner surface of the skull.\r\n\r\nThe middle meningeal artery gives off several branches, including the anterior and posterior branches, which supply the meninges and bones of the cranial vault. It also gives rise to a prominent branch called the **middle meningeal artery** that supplies the dura mater and plays a significant role in the blood supply to the brain.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 842.","responses":[{"text":"Sphenopalatine artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle meningeal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasopalatine artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accessory meningeal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater palatine artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1969,"text":"The transverse facial artery is a branch of which of the following?","explanation":"The **transverse facial artery** is a branch of the **superficial temporal artery**.\r\n\r\nThe superficial temporal artery is a major branch of the **external carotid artery**. It arises in the parotid gland and courses superiorly along the side of the head, giving off several branches along its course. One of these branches is the transverse facial artery.\r\n\r\nThe transverse facial artery takes a tortuous course across the face, passing horizontally across the masseter muscle. It supplies the skin and superficial structures of the face, including the parotid duct, buccinator muscle, and adjacent regions. It gives off small branches that anastomose with other facial arteries, contributing to the rich vascular network of the face.","reference":"(1) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 864. \r\n  \r\n(2) Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 919.","responses":[{"text":"Posterior auricular artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial temporal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Occipital artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1979,"text":"Lymph from tongue drain in which of the following lymph nodes?","explanation":"The lymph from the tongue drains into the **jugulo-omohyoid lymph nodes**.\r\n\r\nThe jugulo-omohyoid lymph nodes, also known as the superior deep cervical lymph nodes, are located near the junction of the internal jugular vein and the omohyoid muscle. They receive lymphatic drainage from the tongue, as well as from the floor of the mouth and the sublingual region. \r\n\r\nThese lymph nodes are part of the deep cervical lymph node chain, which plays a crucial role in draining lymph from the head and neck region. The lymphatic vessels from the tongue converge and pass through the jugulo-omohyoid nodes before continuing their drainage into other nodes along the lymphatic pathways.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1028.","responses":[{"text":"Deep cervical","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supraclavicular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submental","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jugulodigastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jugulo-omohyoid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2004,"text":"A young man had a car accident and came to the emergency room (ER) with a fracture of a facial bone that is unpaired. Which bone is involved?","explanation":"The **mandible**, also known as the lower jawbone, is the only movable bone in the skull and is unpaired. It forms the lower part of the face and plays a crucial role in functions such as chewing, speaking, and facial expression.\r\n\r\nFractures of the mandible commonly occur due to trauma, such as car accidents or physical assaults. The mandible can fracture at various sites, including the body, angle, ramus, or condyle.\r\n\r\nIn the given scenario, a fracture of an unpaired facial bone suggests a fracture of the mandible. The diagnosis can be confirmed through clinical examination, radiographic imaging, and other diagnostic tests.\r\n\r\nManagement of mandible fractures depends on the location and severity of the fracture, and may involve immobilization, reduction, and surgical intervention if necessary.","reference":"(1) Gómez Roselló E, Quiles Granado AM, Artajona Garcia M, et al. Facial fractures: classification and highlights for a useful report. Insights into Imaging. Published March 19, 2020. Accessed May 3, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7082488/\r\n\r\n(2) Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 186.","responses":[{"text":"Mandible bone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasal bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lacrimal bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zygomatic bone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2094,"text":"Which of the following is present in the optic canal?","explanation":"The structure that is present in the optic canal is the **ophthalmic artery**.\r\n\r\nThe optic canal is a bony canal located in the sphenoid bone, through which the optic nerve (cranial nerve II) and ophthalmic artery pass. The ophthalmic artery is the first and main branch of the internal carotid artery within the cranial cavity. It supplies blood to the structures within the orbit, including the retina, choroid, and other ocular structures.\r\n\r\nThe ophthalmic artery accompanies the optic nerve through the optic canal and continues into the orbit as the central retinal artery, which supplies the retina. It gives off various branches within the orbit to supply the extraocular muscles, lacrimal gland, and other structures.\r\n\r\nThe presence of the ophthalmic artery in the optic canal is of clinical significance as vascular disorders or compressive lesions affecting this artery can result in visual disturbances and ocular complications.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 923.","responses":[{"text":"Ophthalmic artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Abducens nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lacrimal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Frontal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infraorbital nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2168,"text":"In the case of vitamin A deficiency, keratomalacia occurs. Which of the following characterizes this condition?","explanation":"Keratomalacia is a condition characterized by **dryness and clouding of the cornea** due to severe **vitamin A deficiency**. Vitamin A is essential for maintaining the integrity and health of the epithelial tissues, including the **cornea**. The cornea is the clear, outermost layer of the eye that plays a crucial role in **focusing light onto the retina** for vision.\r\n\r\nIn vitamin A deficiency, the lack of this important nutrient leads to a disruption in the normal functioning of the **epithelial cells in the cornea**. The cornea becomes **dry, loses its clarity**, and may develop **ulcers or other abnormalities**. This can result in vision impairment, including **night blindness (nyctalopia)** and eventually, if left untreated, **complete blindness**.\r\n\r\nThe term \"keratomalacia\" specifically refers to the **softening and degeneration of the cornea** due to vitamin A deficiency. The condition is often associated with other systemic manifestations of vitamin A deficiency, such as **xerophthalmia (dryness of the conjunctiva)** and **Bitot's spots (localized thickening of the conjunctiva)**. Prompt treatment with **vitamin A supplementation** can reverse the ocular manifestations of keratomalacia and prevent further vision loss.","reference":"Chan E, Buzzard J, Helms R, Grigorian AP. Evaluation and clinical course of keratomalacia with descemetocele in a child with autism and vitamin a deficiency. Journal of Pediatric Ophthalmology \u0026 Strabismus. Published November 2020. Accessed April 25, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/medgen/57777","responses":[{"text":"Dryness of conjunctiva and cornea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unable to see in light or dark condition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patient cannot see in low light or in near dark condition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Localized thickening of conjunctiva","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dryness and clouding of cornea","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2231,"text":"An oblique facial cleft is a developmental anomaly that occurs due to failure of fusion of which of the following structures?","explanation":"An oblique facial cleft is a developmental anomaly that occurs due to the failure of fusion between the **maxillary prominence** and the **lateral nasal prominence**. During embryonic development, the face forms through the fusion of various facial prominences, which are bulges of tissue that grow and come together. The maxillary prominence is an important component of the developing face and contributes to the formation of the upper jaw and the sides of the upper lip. The lateral nasal prominence, on the other hand, gives rise to the sides of the nose.\r\n\r\nIn cases of an oblique facial cleft, there is a visible separation or gap between the maxillary and lateral nasal prominences, resulting in a cleft or fissure in the affected area of the face. This anomaly can vary in severity, ranging from a small notch or groove to a more significant cleft extending through the lip and possibly into the palate.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 306.","responses":[{"text":"Two maxillary prominence with each other","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Two mandibular prominence with each other","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary prominence with medial nasal prominence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary prominence with lateral nasal prominence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Two medial nasal prominence with each other","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2241,"text":"Taste buds are present in the following papillae except:","explanation":"**Filiform** papillae are the type of papillae that do not contain taste buds. The other types of papillae—**fungiform**, **circumvallate**, and **foliate**—do contain taste buds. \r\n\r\nFiliform papillae serve a different function, providing mechanical support to the tongue and contributing to its texture. Taste buds, which are specialized sensory structures, are responsible for detecting taste sensations. They are primarily located within the fungiform, circumvallate, and foliate papillae. The fungiform papillae are mushroom-shaped and scattered across the anterior part of the tongue, while the circumvallate papillae are larger and form a V-shaped row at the back of the tongue. The foliate papillae are found on the lateral aspects of the posterior part of the tongue.","reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 171.","responses":[{"text":"Filliform","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fulliform","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Circumvalate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foliate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fungiform","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2275,"text":"Which is not present in the carotid sheath?","explanation":"The **external jugular vein** is not present in the carotid sheath.\r\n\r\nThe carotid sheath is a fibrous connective tissue sheath that contains important structures in the neck. It is located on the lateral aspect of the neck and extends from the base of the skull to the superior mediastinum. The structures that are typically found within the carotid sheath include the **internal carotid artery**, **internal jugular vein**, and **vagus nerve**.\r\n\r\nThe internal carotid artery is a major blood vessel that supplies blood to the brain. It travels through the carotid sheath alongside the internal jugular vein, which is responsible for draining deoxygenated blood from the brain, face, and neck. The vagus nerve, also known as the tenth cranial nerve, is a mixed nerve that carries motor and sensory fibers to various organs in the neck, thorax, and abdomen.\r\n\r\nThe external jugular vein, on the other hand, is not located within the carotid sheath. It is a superficial vein that is visible on the lateral surface of the neck and drains blood from the scalp and face.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 997.","responses":[{"text":"External jugular vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagus nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal jugular vein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2280,"text":"The infraorbital foramen is an opening in which of the following bones?","explanation":"The **infraorbital foramen** is an opening in the **maxillary bone**. It is located in the floor of the orbit, just below the infraorbital margin. The foramen serves as a passageway for the **infraorbital nerve**, which is a branch of the **maxillary division** of the trigeminal nerve (CN V2). The infraorbital nerve provides sensory innervation to the lower eyelid, upper lip, and lateral aspect of the nose.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 856.","responses":[{"text":"Maxillary bone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethmoid bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zygomatic bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater wing of the sphenoid bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Frontal bone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2286,"text":"Which of the following muscles is not supplied by the mandibular nerve?","explanation":"The **buccinator muscle** is not supplied by the **mandibular nerve** (CN V3). The buccinator muscle is innervated by the **facial nerve** (CN VII). The buccinator muscle forms the lateral wall of the oral cavity and plays a role in mastication by keeping the cheeks taut.\r\n\r\nThe other muscles listed in the options, namely the **lateral pterygoid, temporalis, masseter**, and **medial pterygoid**, are all supplied by the mandibular nerve (CN V3). The mandibular nerve is the largest branch of the trigeminal nerve and provides motor innervation to the muscles of mastication.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 977.","responses":[{"text":"Medial pterygoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Temporalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral pterygoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Masseter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccinator","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2305,"text":"Which muscle takes part in the formation of palatine aponeurosis?","explanation":"The **tensor veli palatini** muscle takes part in the formation of the palatine aponeurosis.\r\n\r\nThe palatine aponeurosis is a thin, fibrous sheet that extends horizontally across the posterior part of the hard palate. It plays a role in elevating the soft palate and closing off the nasopharynx during swallowing and speaking. The palatine aponeurosis is an important structure in maintaining the integrity of the soft palate and its proper functioning.\r\n\r\nThe tensor veli palatini muscle is one of the muscles involved in the soft palate's movement and function. It arises from the cartilaginous part of the auditory tube (eustachian tube) and the adjacent sphenoid bone. It courses downward and laterally to insert into the palatine aponeurosis. Contraction of the tensor veli palatini muscle helps to tense and flatten the soft palate, contributing to the closure of the nasopharynx during swallowing and speaking.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 946.","responses":[{"text":"Musculus uvulae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatoglossus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatopharyngeus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tensor veli palatini","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tensor tympani","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2322,"text":"A person injures his mandible (ramus) in an accident. Which boundary of the wall of the infratemporal fossa does it form?","explanation":"The mandible forms part of the **lateral wall** of the infratemporal fossa. The infratemporal fossa is a space located deep to the zygomatic arch and posterior to the maxilla. It is bounded by several structures, including the lateral pterygoid plate, the greater wing of the sphenoid bone, the ramus of the mandible, and the deep temporal fascia.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 981.","responses":[{"text":"Posterior wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral wall","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior wall","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2331,"text":"Aphakia is associated with which of the following?","explanation":"**Aphakia** refers to the absence or loss of the lens in the eye. It typically occurs as a result of surgical removal or traumatic injury to the lens. Since the lens plays a crucial role in focusing light onto the retina, the absence of the lens affects the refractive power of the eye.\r\n\r\nAphakia is associated with **hypermetropia** (also known as farsightedness). Hypermetropia is a refractive error where the eye has difficulty focusing on nearby objects due to the insufficient curvature of the cornea or the eyeball being too short. In aphakic eyes, the absence of the lens reduces the total refractive power of the eye, resulting in a significant degree of hypermetropia.\r\n\r\nPatients with aphakia often require corrective lenses or contact lenses to compensate for the refractive error and improve their vision.","reference":"Majumdar S, Tripathy K. Hyperopia. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed May 12, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560716/","responses":[{"text":"Glaucoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudoaphakia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Astigmatism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyphema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypermetropia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2335,"text":"In lateral view of an X-ray of the head, a physician notices the meeting point of parietooccipital, occipitomastoid, and lambdoid sutures. What is this point called?","explanation":"The point of meeting between the parietooccipital, occipitomastoid, and lambdoid sutures in the lateral view of an X-ray of the head is known as the **asterion**. The asterion is an anatomical landmark located at the junction of the parietal, occipital, and temporal bones.\r\n\r\nIdentifying the asterion is important in clinical practice, particularly in neurosurgery and radiology, as it serves as a reference point for various surgical approaches and diagnostic interpretations. For example, in neurosurgery, the asterion is used as a landmark for locating the transverse sinus during procedures.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 836.","responses":[{"text":"Asterion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lambda","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bregma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2364,"text":"Which of the following nerves provide sensory supply to the skin overlying the angle of the mandible?","explanation":"The **greater auricular nerve** provides sensory supply to the skin overlying the angle of the mandible. It is a branch of the cervical plexus, specifically arising from the second and third cervical spinal nerves (C2-C3). \r\n\r\nThe greater auricular nerve travels superficially along the posterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle and ascends towards the angle of the mandible. It innervates the skin overlying the lower part of the ear, the angle of the mandible, and the adjacent area of the parotid region.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 857.","responses":[{"text":"Mandibular branch of trigeminal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lesser occipital nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary branch of trigeminal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater auricular nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater occipital nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2365,"text":"A person presents with his right eye looking \"down and out\" with double vision (diplopia) when looking at the right. He has a lesion in which of the following nerves?","explanation":"The patient's presentation of the right eye being \"down and out\" with diplopia on right gaze suggests a **lesion of the right oculomotor nerve** (cranial nerve III). The oculomotor nerve innervates several extraocular muscles responsible for eye movements, including the superior rectus, medial rectus, inferior rectus, and inferior oblique muscles.\r\n\r\nA lesion of the oculomotor nerve can result in various deficits, including **drooping of the eyelid** (ptosis), **inability to move the eye medially** (limitation of adduction), and **downward deviation of the eye** (inferior displacement). These findings are consistent with the patient's \"down and out\" eye position and diplopia on right gaze.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 350, 351.","responses":[{"text":"Right oculomotor nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right trochlear nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left trigeminal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left trochlear nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left oculomotor nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2493,"text":"The submandibular lymph nodes are present in which triangle?","explanation":"The submandibular lymph nodes are located in the **digastric triangle**, also known as the submandibular triangle. This triangular region is formed by the anterior and posterior bellies of the digastric muscle and the inferior border of the mandible.\r\n\r\nThe submandibular lymph nodes are part of the lymphatic drainage system of the head and neck. They receive lymphatic vessels from various structures in the oral cavity, sublingual region, tongue, and submandibular gland. These nodes play a crucial role in filtering lymph fluid and trapping pathogens, foreign particles, and cancer cells.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 1022.","responses":[{"text":"Submental triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Digastric triangle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Muscular triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carotid triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Omohyoid triangle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2498,"text":"The suspensory ligaments of the eye are an extension of which of the following?","explanation":"The suspensory ligaments of the eye, also known as the **suspensory ligament of the lens**, are extensions of **Tenon's capsule**. Tenon's capsule is a connective tissue layer that surrounds the eyeball and separates it from the surrounding orbital structures.\r\n\r\nThe suspensory ligaments play a crucial role in supporting and stabilizing the lens within the eye. They attach to the ciliary body, which is a muscular structure located just behind the iris. The ciliary body produces aqueous humor and contains the ciliary muscle, which is responsible for accommodation (changing the shape of the lens to focus on near or distant objects).\r\n\r\nBy connecting the lens to the ciliary body, the suspensory ligaments exert tension on the lens and help maintain its shape and position. They assist in the process of accommodation by allowing the ciliary muscle to alter the tension on the lens, enabling the eye to focus on objects at different distances.","reference":"Hu S, Colley P. Surgical orbital anatomy. Semin Plast Surg. 2019;33(2):85-91. doi:10.1055/s-0039-1685476\r\nhttps://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6486368","responses":[{"text":"Orbital septum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tenon's capsule","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep fascia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Periorbital fascia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial fascia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2504,"text":"A man received a strong blow to the anterior aspect of the mandible during a fight. The tympanic plate of the external auditory meatus was affected. The temporomandibular joint has undergone which type of dislocation?","explanation":"The TMJ is a synovial joint that allows for the movement of the mandible, enabling actions such as opening and closing the mouth, chewing, and speaking. It is formed by the articulation of the condyle of the mandible with the mandibular fossa of the temporal bone, along with the articular disc that separates the two bones.\r\n\r\nA **posterior dislocation** of the TMJ occurs when the mandibular condyle is forced posteriorly beyond the articular eminence of the temporal bone. This can happen due to a strong blow to the anterior aspect of the mandible, which causes the mandible to dislocate posteriorly.\r\n\r\nPatients with a posterior TMJ dislocation often present with the jaw locked in an open position and an inability to close the mouth. They may also experience pain and difficulty in moving the jaw.","reference":"Chung KW, Chung HM, Halliday NL. BRS: Gross Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer Health; 2015: 368.","responses":[{"text":"Superior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2505,"text":"A student is studying about a muscle that forms the boundaries of both anterior and posterior triangles. Which of the following is the appropriate muscle?","explanation":"The appropriate muscle that forms the boundaries of both the anterior and posterior triangles is the **sternocleidomastoid muscle**. This muscle is located in the neck and has a prominent position. It originates from the sternum and clavicle and inserts on the mastoid process of the temporal bone.\r\n\r\nThe sternocleidomastoid muscle divides the neck into two triangles: the anterior triangle and the posterior triangle. The anterior triangle is located in front of the muscle, while the posterior triangle is located behind it. These triangles serve as important anatomical landmarks in the neck.\r\n\r\nThe sternocleidomastoid muscle has multiple functions. It acts to flex and rotate the head, as well as elevate the sternum during forced inhalation. Additionally, it plays a role in maintaining proper posture.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 998.","responses":[{"text":"Levator scapulae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sternocleidomastoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Suprahyoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infrahyoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trapezius","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2526,"text":"Which of the following muscles causes forceful closure of the eyes?","explanation":"The muscle that causes forceful closure of the eyes is the **orbital part of the orbicularis oculi** muscle. The orbicularis oculi is a facial muscle that encircles the eye and consists of three parts: orbital, palpebral, and lacrimal.\r\n\r\nThe orbital part of the orbicularis oculi is responsible for forcefully closing the eyelids. It contracts during activities such as blinking, squinting, and forcefully closing the eyes to protect them from foreign objects or excessive light. It plays a crucial role in maintaining the health and integrity of the eyes.\r\n\r\nThe palpebral part of the orbicularis oculi is responsible for gentle closure of the eyelids, while the lacrimal part contributes to the drainage of tears from the eye.","reference":"Halliday NL, Chung HM. BRS: Gross Anatomy. 9th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 363.","responses":[{"text":"Procerus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of them","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lacrimal part of orbicularis oculi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orbital part of orbicularis oculi","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Palpebral part of orbicularis oculi","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2533,"text":"Which structure does not pass through the superior orbital fissure?","explanation":"The **superior orbital fissure** is a bony opening located in the posterior part of the orbit, between the greater and lesser wings of the sphenoid bone. It serves as a pathway for several important structures that innervate the eye and control its movements.\r\n\r\nThe structures that pass through the superior orbital fissure include the oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III), which supplies most of the extraocular muscles except for the superior oblique and the lateral rectus muscles. The abducens nerve (cranial nerve VI) innervates the lateral rectus muscle, while the trochlear nerve (cranial nerve IV) innervates the superior oblique muscle. The superior ophthalmic vein, which drains blood from the orbit, also passes through the superior orbital fissure.\r\n\r\nHowever, the **optic nerve**, responsible for transmitting visual information from the retina to the brain, does not pass through the superior orbital fissure. Instead, it enters the orbit through the optic canal, a separate opening in the lesser wing of the sphenoid bone.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 193.","responses":[{"text":"Abducens nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Optic nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior ophthalmic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oculomotor nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trochlear nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2534,"text":"A girl is facing pre-pubertal acne. The doctor warns her about not squeezing any pimples and prescribes her some special cream for the tip of the nose and the upper lip region acne. What is the most likely reason?","explanation":"The most likely reason the doctor prescribed a special cream for the tip of the nose and the upper lip region acne is that this area has **direct dural venous drainage**. Acne in this region can be of concern due to its proximity to the facial veins, which have direct communication with the intracranial dural sinuses.\r\n\r\nThe veins in the area of the tip of the nose and upper lip region, known as the \"dangerous area of the face,\" lack the protective valve mechanism found in other facial veins. Consequently, any infection or inflammation in this region has the potential to spread directly to the intracranial venous sinuses, such as the cavernous sinus. This can lead to serious complications, including cavernous sinus thrombosis, which is a life-threatening condition.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 909.","responses":[{"text":"This area requires more special care than the others","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"This area is more prone to acne","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"This area is richly vascularized","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"This area has direct dural venous drainage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2543,"text":"Umami taste fibers are related to?","explanation":"Umami taste fibers are primarily related to **glutamate**. Glutamate is an amino acid and Umami is one of the five basic tastes, alongside sweet, sour, salty, and bitter. Umami, often described as a savory or meaty taste, is largely attributed to the presence of glutamate in food.\r\n\r\nGlutamate receptors on the taste buds detect the presence of glutamate molecules and initiate the transmission of signals to the brain, resulting in the perception of umami taste. Glutamate is naturally found in various foods such as meat, fish, mushrooms, and certain vegetables.\r\n\r\nThe recognition of umami taste is essential for the enjoyment and satisfaction of savory flavors in our diet. It adds depth and richness to food, enhancing its palatability.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 675-676.","responses":[{"text":"Organic substances containing nitrogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fructose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alkaloids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2553,"text":"Myopia is corrected by what type of lens?","explanation":"Myopia, commonly known as nearsightedness, is a refractive error of the eye that causes distant objects to appear blurred, while close objects can be seen clearly. It occurs when the eyeball is longer than normal or the cornea is excessively curved, causing light to focus in front of the retina instead of directly on it.\r\n\r\nTo correct myopia, a **concave lens** is used. A concave lens is thinner at the center and thicker at the edges, causing light rays entering the eye to diverge before reaching the lens of the eye. This divergence helps to shift the focal point backward onto the retina, allowing for clear vision of distant objects.\r\n\r\nWhen a person with myopia wears concave lenses, the lenses help to properly refract light and focus it directly on the retina, resulting in clearer distance vision. The concave lens helps to correct the refractive error by diverging the incoming light and moving the focal point to the correct position on the retina.","reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 641.","responses":[{"text":"Convex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Imaginary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mixed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Concave","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9366,"text":"Which of the following structures pass through the lateral wall of the pterygopalatine fossa?","explanation":"The **terminal branches of the maxillary artery** pass through the lateral wall of the pterygopalatine fossa.\r\n\r\nThe pterygopalatine fossa is a small space located in the deep part of the skull, behind the maxilla and medial to the pterygoid processes of the sphenoid bone. It serves as a conduit for several important structures including nerves, blood vessels, and lymphatics.\r\n\r\nThe lateral wall of the pterygopalatine fossa is traversed by the terminal branches of the maxillary artery. These branches include the infraorbital artery, posterior superior alveolar artery, and descending palatine artery. They supply blood to various structures in the region, including the face, maxillary teeth, and the palate.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 959.","responses":[{"text":"Maxillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Terminal branches of maxillary artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior alveolar artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Branches of facial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep temporal arteries","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9400,"text":"Which of the following structures forms the anterior wall of the pterygopalatine fossa?","explanation":"The **posterior surface of the maxilla** forms the anterior wall of the pterygopalatine fossa.\r\n\r\nThe pterygopalatine fossa is a small space located in the deep part of the skull, behind the maxilla and medial to the pterygoid processes of the sphenoid bone. It serves as a conduit for several important structures including nerves, blood vessels, and lymphatics.\r\n\r\nThe anterior wall of the pterygopalatine fossa is formed by the posterior surface of the maxilla. This wall is located behind the posterior wall of the maxillary sinus. It separates the pterygopalatine fossa from the maxillary sinus.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 982.","responses":[{"text":"Posterior surface of maxilla","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Zygomatic arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial pterygoid plate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infratemporal fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral pterygoid plate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9401,"text":"Which part of the mandible forms the temporomandibular joint?","explanation":"The **condylar process** of the mandible forms the temporomandibular joint (TMJ).\r\n\r\nThe TMJ is a synovial joint that connects the mandible to the temporal bone of the skull. It allows for the movement of the jaw, including opening and closing of the mouth, as well as side-to-side and forward-backward movements during chewing and speaking.\r\n\r\nThe condylar process is the rounded, bony projection located at the posterior end of the mandible. It articulates with the mandibular fossa of the temporal bone, forming the TMJ. The joint is stabilized by ligaments and surrounded by a fibrous capsule, which contains synovial fluid to reduce friction during movement.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 925.","responses":[{"text":"Coronoid process","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ramus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Condylar process","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Angle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9402,"text":"Which of the following is not a direct branch of the external carotid artery?","explanation":"The **external carotid artery** is a major branch of the common carotid artery and gives rise to several branches that supply blood to various structures in the head and neck. These branches include the facial artery, ascending pharyngeal artery, lingual artery, and maxillary artery.\r\n\r\nHowever, the **sphenopalatine artery** is not a direct branch of the external carotid artery. It is actually a branch of the maxillary artery, which itself is a branch of the external carotid artery. The sphenopalatine artery supplies blood to the nasal cavity, palate, and surrounding structures.","reference":"Halliday NL, M C Harold, Won C Kyung. BRS: Gross Anatomy. 10th ed. Wolters Kluwer Health/Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2020: 353, 354, 373, 374.","responses":[{"text":"Ascending pharyngeal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingual artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphenopalatine artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9403,"text":"What is the position of the macula lutea relative to the optic disc in the eyeball?","explanation":"The **macula lutea** is located **lateral** to the optic disc in the eyeball.\r\n\r\nThe macula lutea is a small, oval-shaped area located in the central part of the retina. It is responsible for central vision and contains a high concentration of cone cells, which are specialized photoreceptor cells for color vision and visual acuity. The macula lutea is slightly **lateral** to the optic disc.\r\n\r\nThe optic disc, also known as the blind spot, is the site where the optic nerve exits the eye and contains no photoreceptor cells. It is located on the **medial** side of the posterior pole of the eyeball. The macula lutea is situated slightly **lateral** to the optic disc, closer to the temporal side of the eyeball.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 905.","responses":[{"text":"Inferior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9408,"text":"Anesthesia in retromolar fossa primarily blocks which of the following nerves?","explanation":"The **retromolar fossa** is a triangular depression located behind the last molar tooth in the mandible. Anesthesia in this region primarily blocks the **buccal nerve**, which is a branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V). The buccal nerve provides sensory innervation to the buccal mucosa, skin of the cheek, and the mucous membrane of the lower lip.\r\n\r\nBlocking the buccal nerve can be achieved through local anesthesia techniques, such as an inferior alveolar nerve block or an infiltration technique, to provide pain relief and numbness in the retromolar fossa and surrounding areas.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 870.","responses":[{"text":"Submandibular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingual nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mental nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior alveolar nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9409,"text":"Which of the following does not take part in the formation of the carotid sheath?","explanation":"The **carotid sheath** is a fascial structure that encloses and provides a common sheath for the internal carotid artery, internal jugular vein, and vagus nerve (cranial nerve X). It plays an important role in providing support and protection to these structures as they traverse the neck.\r\n\r\nThe carotid sheath is formed by three layers of deep cervical fascia: the investing layer, pretracheal layer, and prevertebral layer. These fascial layers envelop and surround the structures within the carotid sheath.\r\n\r\nThe **parotid gland sheath**, on the other hand, is a separate fascial structure that surrounds and supports the parotid gland, which is a salivary gland located in the lateral region of the face. It is not directly involved in the formation of the carotid sheath.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 991.","responses":[{"text":"Investing layer of fascia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parotid gland sheath","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevertebral layer of fascia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pretracheal layer of fascia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9410,"text":"Fracture of mandible most likely results in the damage of which of the following nerves?","explanation":"The **inferior alveolar nerve** is a branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V3). It provides sensory innervation to the lower teeth, lower lip, and chin. \r\n\r\nA fracture of the mandible, particularly in the region of the body or angle, can potentially damage the inferior alveolar nerve. This can occur due to direct trauma or compression of the nerve by displaced bone fragments. The resulting injury to the nerve can lead to numbness or altered sensation in the areas it supplies.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 939.","responses":[{"text":"Inferior alveolar nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingual nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9412,"text":"A nerve winds around the styloid process and carries postganglionic parasympathetic fibers which stimulate salivary secretion in the submandibular and sublingual glands. What is the name of the given nerve?","explanation":"The **chorda tympani** is a branch of the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) that carries taste fibers from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue and parasympathetic fibers to the submandibular and sublingual glands. It is an important nerve involved in the regulation of salivary secretion.\r\n\r\nThe chorda tympani passes through the middle ear and wraps around the **styloid process** of the temporal bone. It then courses forward and joins the lingual nerve (a branch of the trigeminal nerve) in the infratemporal fossa. From there, it continues to the tongue, carrying taste information and parasympathetic fibers.\r\n\r\nThe parasympathetic fibers carried by the chorda tympani stimulate salivary secretion in the submandibular and sublingual glands, contributing to the production of saliva. Therefore, damage or dysfunction of the chorda tympani can result in dryness of the mouth and decreased salivary flow.","reference":"(1) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 929.\r\n(2) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Elsevier; 2020: 987.","responses":[{"text":"Facial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingual nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chorda tympani","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep petrosal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9415,"text":"Maxillary sinus drains into which of the following?","explanation":"The **maxillary sinus**, also known as the antrum of Highmore, is one of the paranasal sinuses located within the maxillary bone. It is the largest of the paranasal sinuses and is positioned below the orbit and above the alveolar process of the maxilla.\r\n\r\nThe maxillary sinus drains into the **middle nasal meatus** through an opening called the **maxillary sinus ostium**. This ostium is located high on the lateral wall of the middle nasal meatus, near the superior border of the middle concha. It serves as the passageway for the drainage of mucus and secretions from the maxillary sinus into the nasal cavity.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 971.","responses":[{"text":"Inferior nasal meatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spheno-ethmoidal recess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior nasal meatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle nasal meatus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Semilunar hiatus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9416,"text":"The nose has a rich vascular supply. Which of the following arteries does not directly supply the nose?","explanation":"The nose receives its blood supply from various arteries that contribute to its rich vascular network. These arteries include the **anterior ethmoidal artery, posterior ethmoidal artery, sphenopalatine artery, and lateral nasal arteries**.\r\n\r\nHowever, the **descending palatine artery does not directly supply the nose**. It is a branch of the maxillary artery and primarily provides blood to the soft palate, palatine tonsils, and part of the nasal septum. The descending palatine artery descends along the lateral wall of the nasopharynx, but it does not have direct branches that supply the nasal cavity.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1072, 1073.","responses":[{"text":"Sphenopalatine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior ethmoidal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Descending palatine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior ethmoidal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral nasal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9418,"text":"A person feels pain when drinking hot tea. On examination, the central part of the lower lip has an ulcer and associated lymph nodes are swollen. Which nodes are involved?","explanation":"The **submental nodes** are a group of lymph nodes located in the submental region, which is the central part of the lower lip and the chin. These nodes drain lymphatic fluid from the corresponding area, including the lower lip, chin, and the floor of the mouth.\r\n\r\nIn the given scenario, the presence of an ulcer in the central part of the lower lip suggests a possible infection or inflammation in that area. When the immune system detects such an infection, it triggers an immune response, leading to the enlargement and tenderness of the regional lymph nodes.\r\n\r\nThe submental nodes are the primary drainage nodes for the central part of the lower lip. Therefore, their enlargement and tenderness indicate their involvement in the immune response to the infection or inflammation causing the ulcer.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 937.","responses":[{"text":"Superficial cervical lymph nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep cervical lymph nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submental nodes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9420,"text":"Preganglionic fibers for pupillary reflex reach ciliary ganglion where they synapse and form short ciliary nerves (postganglionic fibers) that innervate the eye. Preganglionic fibers reach ciliary ganglion by which of the following nerves?","explanation":"The **oculomotor nerve** (cranial nerve III) plays a crucial role in the pupillary reflex. Preganglionic fibers carrying parasympathetic innervation for pupillary constriction originate from the Edinger-Westphal nucleus, which is located in the midbrain. These preganglionic fibers travel through the oculomotor nerve to reach the ciliary ganglion, where they synapse with the postganglionic neurons.\r\n\r\nWithin the ciliary ganglion, the preganglionic fibers form synapses with the postganglionic neurons, and the resulting short ciliary nerves carry the postganglionic fibers to the eye. These postganglionic fibers innervate the sphincter pupillae muscle, which causes constriction of the pupil in response to light stimulation.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that the oculomotor nerve is responsible for other functions as well, including innervation of other extraocular muscles that control eye movement. However, in the context of the pupillary reflex, the oculomotor nerve is the nerve through which the preganglionic fibers reach the ciliary ganglion.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 934, 935.","responses":[{"text":"Optic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasociliary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nerve to inferior oblique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oculomotor nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nerve to inferior rectus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9422,"text":"For near vision, the lens is accommodated to attain increased convexity. Which of the following muscle contracts to help in this action?","explanation":"During near vision, the lens needs to adjust its shape to increase its convexity in order to focus light rays onto the retina. This process is called accommodation. The **ciliary muscle** plays a crucial role in accommodation.\r\n\r\nWhen the ciliary muscle contracts, it causes relaxation and release of tension on the suspensory ligaments (zonular fibers) that are attached to the lens. This allows the lens to become more rounded and increases its refractive power, enabling the eye to focus on near objects.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the dilator pupillae and sphincter pupillae muscles are responsible for controlling the size of the pupil, not for accommodation. The dilator pupillae dilates the pupil, while the sphincter pupillae constricts the pupil.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 935.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ciliary muscle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilator pupillae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphincter pupillae","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9423,"text":"A 20-year-old boy has an accident. In the accident, the floor of the temporal fossa is fractured. Which of the following structures is not affected?","explanation":"In the given scenario, if the **floor of the temporal fossa** is fractured, it is likely to involve the bones that contribute to the floor of the fossa. The floor of the temporal fossa is formed by several bones, including the squamous part of the temporal bone, the greater wing of the sphenoid, and the frontal bone. \r\n\r\nThe parietal bone is not directly involved in the floor of the temporal fossa, so it would not be affected by the fracture.\r\n\r\nHowever, the **lesser wing of the sphenoid** is not part of the floor of the temporal fossa. It is a bony structure located in the anterior cranial fossa and forms part of the middle cranial fossa. Therefore, it would not be affected by a fracture of the temporal fossa floor.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 924.","responses":[{"text":"Squamous part of temporal  bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Frontal bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parietal bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lesser wing of sphenoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater wing of sphenoid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9424,"text":"A person meets an accident and loses all the salivary activity of the submandibular gland. The preganglionic parasympathetic secretomotor fibers to this gland are carried by which of the following nerves?","explanation":"The submandibular gland receives preganglionic parasympathetic secretomotor fibers from the chorda tympani, a branch of the facial nerve (CN VII). The chorda tympani travels with the **lingual nerve**, a branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (CN V3).\r\n\r\nThe preganglionic fibers from the facial nerve synapse in the submandibular ganglion, located near the submandibular gland. Postganglionic parasympathetic fibers then innervate the submandibular gland, stimulating salivary secretion.\r\n\r\nIn the given scenario, if the person loses all salivary activity of the submandibular gland, it suggests damage to the lingual nerve carrying the preganglionic parasympathetic fibers. This can result from an accident affecting the lingual nerve's course or function.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 929.","responses":[{"text":"Inferior alveolar nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submental nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glossopharyngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingual nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Auriculotemporal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9594,"text":"A patient has swelling on his face with midface mobility and malocclusion of his teeth with anterior open bite. What kind of fracture is described here/what bone is involved?","explanation":"The description provided in the question, including swelling on the face, midface mobility, and malocclusion of teeth with an anterior open bite, is suggestive of a fracture involving the **maxillofacial region**. Maxillofacial fractures can occur due to various causes, such as trauma or accidents.\r\n\r\nThe maxillofacial region encompasses the bones of the face, including the **maxilla**, **zygomatic bones**, **nasal bones**, and other associated structures. Fractures in this region can affect different bones and structures, leading to characteristic signs and symptoms. In the given scenario, the presence of midface mobility and malocclusion of teeth with an anterior open bite suggests involvement of the **maxilla**. The maxilla forms a significant portion of the midface and plays a crucial role in dental occlusion. Fractures in this area can result in facial swelling, mobility, and misalignment of the teeth.","reference":"Phillips BJ, Turco LM. Le fort fractures: a collective review. Bull Emerg Trauma. 2017;5(4):221-230. \r\nhttps://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5694594/","responses":[{"text":"Fracture of sphenoid body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture of nasal bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fracture of zygomatic arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillofacial fracture","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9595,"text":"Which of the following is true about the common carotid artery?","explanation":"The **correct** statement about the common carotid artery is that it **divides into the internal and external carotid artery at the upper border of the thyroid cartilage**. The common carotid artery is a major blood vessel that supplies blood to the head and neck. It arises from the aortic arch on the **left side** and from the **brachiocephalic trunk** on the **right side**.\r\n\r\nAs the common carotid artery ascends in the neck, it gives off branches along its course, such as the **thyroid artery** which supplies the thyroid gland. However, the common carotid artery itself does not have a dilatation just after its initiation below the bifurcation. Instead, it forms a **bifurcation** at the level of the upper border of the thyroid cartilage, dividing into the **internal carotid artery** and the **external carotid artery**. The internal carotid artery supplies the brain, while the external carotid artery supplies the face, scalp, and neck structures.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1000.","responses":[{"text":"It supplies a branch to the thyroid gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It divides into internal and external carotid artery at the upper border of thyroid cartilage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It has a dilatation on it just after its initiation below the bifurcation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At the left side, common carotid artery arises from the brachiocephalic trunk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At the right side, common carotid artery arises from the arch of aorta","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9596,"text":"Which of the following is not a content of the pterygopalatine fossa?","explanation":"The **inferior alveolar artery** is not a content of the pterygopalatine fossa. The pterygopalatine fossa is a small space located deep within the skull, posterior to the maxilla and inferior to the apex of the orbit. It serves as a conduit for various structures involved in the sensory innervation of the face and the blood supply to the oral and nasal cavities.\r\n\r\nThe contents of the pterygopalatine fossa include:\r\n\r\n1. **Pterygopalatine ganglion**: Also known as the sphenopalatine ganglion, it is a parasympathetic ganglion that provides innervation to the lacrimal gland, nasal glands, and pharyngeal glands.\r\n\r\n2. **Nerve to pterygoid canal**: This nerve, a branch of the maxillary nerve (V2), passes through the pterygopalatine fossa and enters the pterygoid canal to provide sensory innervation to the posterior part of the hard palate.\r\n\r\n3. **Zygomatic nerve**: This branch of the maxillary nerve (V2) passes through the fossa and provides sensory innervation to the skin over the zygomatic bone and the temporal region.\r\n\r\nThe **inferior alveolar artery** is not a content of the pterygopalatine fossa. It is a branch of the maxillary artery that enters the mandibular foramen to supply the lower teeth and surrounding structures.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 980-986.","responses":[{"text":"Inferior alveolar artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterygopalatine ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nerve to pterygoid canal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zygomatic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9598,"text":"Which of the following muscles is attached to the posterior margin of the eyelid?","explanation":"The muscle attached to the posterior margin of the eyelid is the **levator palpebrae superioris**. This muscle is responsible for raising the upper eyelid (eyelid elevation) and maintaining an open position of the eye. \r\n\r\nThe levator palpebrae superioris originates from the lesser wing of the sphenoid bone, near the optic canal. It travels anteriorly and inserts into the superior tarsal plate of the upper eyelid. Contraction of this muscle results in elevation of the eyelid, allowing for a wider field of vision.\r\n\r\nThe other muscles listed are involved in different movements of the eye. The lateral rectus muscle abducts the eye, the medial rectus muscle adducts the eye, and the orbicularis oculi muscle closes the eyelids. None of these muscles are directly attached to the posterior margin of the eyelid.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 918, 919.","responses":[{"text":"Levator palpebrae superioris","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral rectus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial rectus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orbicularis oculi","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9599,"text":"Which of the following will not be affected by damage to the superior salivatory nucleus in the pons and facial nerve nucleus lesion?","explanation":"Damage to the superior salivatory nucleus in the pons and facial nerve nucleus will not affect the **mylohyoid muscle**. \r\n\r\nThe superior salivatory nucleus is responsible for parasympathetic innervation of the salivary glands and lacrimal gland. Lesions affecting this nucleus or the facial nerve nucleus can lead to deficits in salivation and lacrimation. However, the mylohyoid muscle is innervated by the **inferior alveolar nerve**, which is a branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (CN V3). Therefore, damage to the superior salivatory nucleus or facial nerve nucleus would not directly affect the mylohyoid muscle.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 335, 339.","responses":[{"text":"Stapedius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mylohyoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Occipito-frontalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Taste sensation from anterior two thirds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccinator","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9600,"text":"Damage to the right optic tract causes a defect in which field of vision?","explanation":"Damage to the right optic tract causes a defect in the **ipsilateral nasal and contralateral temporal fields of vision**. The optic tracts carry visual information from the optic chiasm to the visual processing centers in the brain.\r\n\r\nAt the optic chiasm, fibers from the nasal half of each retina cross to the opposite side, while fibers from the temporal half remain on the same side. Therefore, damage to the right optic tract would result in a loss of visual input from the right nasal field (corresponding to the right eye) and the left temporal field (corresponding to the left eye). This defect is known as a **homonymous hemianopia**.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 349.","responses":[{"text":"Ipsilateral temporal and contralateral nasal fields","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ipsilateral nasal and contralateral temporal fields","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ipsilateral nasal and ipsilateral temporal fields","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contralateral nasal and contralateral temporal fields","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9601,"text":"Damage to the right optic nerve will lead to which of the following?","explanation":"Damage to the right optic nerve can result in **total blindness in the right eye**. The optic nerve is responsible for transmitting visual information from the retina to the brain. Each optic nerve carries visual signals from the corresponding eye to the visual centers in the brain.\r\n\r\nWhen the right optic nerve is damaged, the transmission of visual information from the right eye is disrupted, leading to a loss of vision in that eye. The left eye, which is served by the intact left optic nerve, can still transmit visual signals to the brain. However, the right eye, which relies on the damaged right optic nerve, will not be able to send visual signals to the brain, resulting in total blindness in that eye.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that the term \"homonymous hemianopia\" refers to the loss of half of the visual field on the same side in both eyes. In the case of optic nerve damage, the loss of vision is specific to the affected eye rather than the visual field as a whole.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 350.","responses":[{"text":"Total blindness in left eye","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bitemporal hemianopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left homonymous hemianopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right homonymous hemianopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total blindness in right eye","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9602,"text":"A patient suffers damage to the orbit resulting in damage to the third cranial nerve. Which of the following signs will be present?","explanation":"Damage to the third cranial nerve (oculomotor nerve) resulting from orbit trauma can lead to specific signs and symptoms. The oculomotor nerve is responsible for innervating several muscles that control eye movements, including the **superior rectus, inferior rectus, medial rectus, and inferior oblique muscles**, as well as the **levator palpebrae superioris muscle**.\r\n\r\nOne of the notable signs of oculomotor nerve damage is **pupillary dilatation (mydriasis)**. The oculomotor nerve carries parasympathetic fibers that innervate the **sphincter pupillae muscle**, which controls pupillary constriction (miosis). When the oculomotor nerve is damaged, the parasympathetic input to the sphincter pupillae muscle is compromised, leading to a dilated pupil.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, damage to the oculomotor nerve can result in **abduction** of the affected eye due to the unopposed action of the lateral rectus muscle, which is innervated by the sixth cranial nerve (abducens nerve). The medial rectus muscle, innervated by the oculomotor nerve, normally opposes the lateral rectus muscle to maintain alignment of the eyes during horizontal gaze.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 350, 351.","responses":[{"text":"Pupillary constriction and adduction of eye","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pupillary dilatation and abduction of eye","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pupillary constriction and abduction of eye","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pupillary dilatation and adduction of eye","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9603,"text":"The patient is having diplopia with restricted movements of the eye whenever he depresses or adducts the eye. Which nerve is affected?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms of diplopia (double vision) with restricted eye movements when depressing or adducting the eye suggest an **affected third cranial nerve**, also known as the oculomotor nerve. The oculomotor nerve innervates several extraocular muscles responsible for eye movements, including the **superior rectus, inferior rectus, medial rectus, and inferior oblique muscles**.\r\n\r\nDamage to the oculomotor nerve can result in **paralysis or weakness of the affected muscles**. In this case, the restriction of eye movements during depression (looking downward) and adduction (looking inward) suggests impairment of the **inferior rectus and medial rectus muscles**. As a result, the patient experiences diplopia because the affected eye is not able to properly align with the unaffected eye, leading to double vision.\r\n\r\nThe oculomotor nerve also innervates the **levator palpebrae superioris muscle**, which raises the eyelid. Dysfunction of this muscle can cause ptosis (drooping of the eyelid).","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 926.","responses":[{"text":"Sixth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fourth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Third","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fifth","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9621,"text":"Which of the following diseases is caused by the deficiency of vitamin A?","explanation":"Xerophthalmia is a disease caused by the deficiency of **vitamin A**. Vitamin A plays a critical role in maintaining the health of various tissues in the body, including the eyes. It is essential for normal vision, particularly in low-light conditions. \r\n\r\nThe deficiency of vitamin A can lead to a range of ocular manifestations, with xerophthalmia being a prominent feature. Xerophthalmia is characterized by **dryness of the conjunctiva and cornea**, which can progress to night blindness and even complete blindness if left untreated. The deficiency affects the production of **rhodopsin**, a visual pigment found in the rod cells of the retina, leading to impaired vision in dim light.\r\n\r\nIn addition to xerophthalmia, vitamin A deficiency can also cause other systemic manifestations such as **impaired immune function** and **skin changes**. It is an important public health concern, particularly in developing countries where malnutrition is prevalent.\r\n\r\nEarly detection and appropriate supplementation of vitamin A are crucial in the management and prevention of xerophthalmia.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Megaloblastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exophthalmos","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Xerophthalmia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hair loss","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemorrhage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9622,"text":"Cochlear implants are used as a treatment for which type of deafness?","explanation":"Cochlear implants are used as a treatment for **sensorineural loss**. Sensorineural hearing loss occurs due to the damage or dysfunction of the cochlea or the auditory nerve pathways. It can be caused by factors such as genetic conditions, noise exposure, certain medications, infections, or aging.\r\n\r\nCochlear implants are electronic devices that bypass the damaged parts of the inner ear and directly stimulate the auditory nerve. They consist of two main components: an external speech processor and an internal implant. The speech processor captures sound signals, processes them into electrical signals, and transmits them to the internal implant. The implant, which is surgically placed in the cochlea, stimulates the auditory nerve fibers, allowing the individual to perceive sound.\r\n\r\nCochlear implants are highly effective in individuals with severe to profound sensorineural hearing loss who do not benefit significantly from conventional hearing aids. By directly stimulating the auditory nerve, cochlear implants can restore the sensation of sound and improve speech understanding in individuals with sensorineural deafness.","reference":"Anastasiadou S, Al Khalili Y. Hearing loss. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 25, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK542323/","responses":[{"text":"Conductive deafness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sensorineural loss","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vestibulocochlear nerve lesion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Otosclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9623,"text":"A hearing aid is most useful in which of the following hearing problems?","explanation":"A hearing aid is most useful in **sensorineural loss**. Sensorineural hearing loss refers to the impairment of the inner ear (cochlea) or the auditory nerve pathways. It can result from various factors such as age-related changes, noise exposure, genetic factors, or certain diseases. \r\n\r\nA hearing aid is designed to amplify sound and improve the perception of sound for individuals with hearing loss. It works by converting sound waves into electrical signals that are then amplified and transmitted to the ear. In sensorineural hearing loss, the underlying problem lies in the damaged or malfunctioning sensory cells of the inner ear or the auditory nerve pathways. By amplifying the sound, a hearing aid can help compensate for the reduced sensitivity of the damaged structures and improve the overall hearing ability.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, a hearing aid is less effective in cases of conductive deafness, where the problem lies in the middle ear or outer ear structures that transmit sound to the inner ear. In such cases, the use of a hearing aid may not provide significant improvement, and alternative interventions such as surgical correction or medical management may be more appropriate.","reference":"Hearing aids. NIDCD. Accessed April 25, 2022. https://www.nidcd.nih.gov/health/hearing-aids","responses":[{"text":"Perceptive deafness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Noise-mediated hearing loss","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presbycusis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sensorineural loss","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Conductive deafness","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9624,"text":"The greatest difference of refractive indices is found at which of the following sites?","explanation":"The greatest difference in refractive indices is found at the **interface between air and the anterior surface of the cornea**. Refractive index refers to the measure of how much light is bent or refracted as it passes through different media. The greater the difference in refractive indices between two adjacent media, the greater the amount of bending that occurs at their interface.\r\n\r\nIn the case of the eye, light enters through the cornea, which is the transparent outermost layer of the eye. The cornea has a high refractive index, and when light transitions from air (which has a lower refractive index) to the cornea, a significant change in the direction of light occurs. This bending of light is essential for focusing it onto the retina, allowing for clear vision.","reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 638, 639.","responses":[{"text":"Between aqueous humor and the anterior surface of lens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Between air and anterior surface of cornea","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Between the posterior surface of lens and vitreous humor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Between posterior surface of cornea and aqueous humor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9625,"text":"Vibrations in the cochlear fluid cause vibration in which of the following structures?","explanation":"Vibrations in the cochlear fluid cause vibration in the **basilar membrane**. The basilar membrane is a crucial structure within the cochlea of the inner ear and plays a vital role in auditory sensation.\r\n\r\nWhen sound waves enter the cochlea, they cause the fluid within the cochlear duct to move. This movement leads to the displacement of the basilar membrane, which is a thin, flexible structure that runs the length of the cochlea. The basilar membrane is tonotopically organized, meaning different regions of the membrane respond preferentially to different frequencies of sound.\r\n\r\nAs the basilar membrane vibrates, it mechanically stimulates the hair cells located on its surface. These hair cells are sensory receptors responsible for converting mechanical vibrations into electrical signals that can be interpreted by the brain as sound. The vibration of the basilar membrane allows for the differentiation of various frequencies and contributes to our perception of pitch.","reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 674,675.","responses":[{"text":"Basilar membrane","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cupula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tectorial membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Otolithic membrane","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9626,"text":"A patient has sensorineural deafness in the right ear. A 'tuning fork' test will indicate which of the following?","explanation":"In a patient with sensorineural deafness in the right ear, the **Weber test** will lateralize to the **left ear**. The Weber test is a simple screening test used to differentiate between conductive and sensorineural hearing loss.\r\n\r\nDuring the Weber test, a tuning fork is placed on the midline of the patient's forehead or on the vertex of the skull. In a normal individual, the sound should be heard equally in both ears or appear to be coming from the center of the head. However, in cases of unilateral sensorineural deafness, where there is damage to the inner ear or auditory nerve, the sound will be perceived louder in the unaffected ear.\r\n\r\nIn this scenario, if the patient has sensorineural deafness in the right ear, the sound from the tuning fork placed on the forehead will be perceived as louder in the left ear. This is because the unaffected left ear is better able to perceive the sound due to its intact sensory pathway.","reference":"Wahid NWB, Hogan CJ, Attia M. Weber test. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 25, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526135/","responses":[{"text":"Negative Rinne's test in left ear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive Rinne's test in right ear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weber's lateralized to right ear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weber's lateralized to left ear","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9627,"text":"A patient has conductive deafness in the left ear. Which of the following findings will help us know this?","explanation":"In a patient with conductive deafness in the left ear, the **Weber test** will lateralize to the **left ear**. The Weber test is a quick and simple screening test used to evaluate whether hearing loss is conductive or sensorineural.\r\n\r\nDuring the Weber test, a tuning fork is placed on the midline of the patient's forehead or on the vertex of the skull. In a normal individual, the sound should be heard equally in both ears, or it should appear to be coming from the center of the head. However, in cases of unilateral conductive deafness, where there is a problem in sound transmission to the inner ear, the sound will be heard louder in the affected ear.\r\n\r\nIn this scenario, if the patient has conductive deafness in the left ear, the sound from the tuning fork placed on the forehead will be perceived as louder in the left ear. This is because the sound is more efficiently conducted through bone conduction to the affected ear, compensating for the loss of sound transmission through the external or middle ear.","reference":"Wahid NWB, Hogan CJ, Attia M. Weber test. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 25, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526135/","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weber's lateralized to right ear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive Rinne's test in right ear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Positive Rinne's test in left ear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weber's lateralized to left ear","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9628,"text":"A person can not listen to low pitch sounds. Which of the following regions is involved?","explanation":"The **helicotrema** is the region of the cochlea that is involved when a person cannot listen to low pitch sounds. The cochlea is the spiral-shaped structure of the inner ear responsible for converting sound vibrations into electrical signals that can be interpreted by the brain.\r\n\r\nWithin the cochlea, there are specialized structures called the **organ of Corti** that contain hair cells responsible for detecting different frequencies of sound. The organ of Corti is located along the length of the cochlear duct, which is divided into three chambers: the scala vestibuli, the scala media (cochlear duct), and the scala tympani. These chambers are separated by the **basilar membrane**.\r\n\r\nLow pitch sounds have longer wavelengths and lower frequencies. When these low pitch sounds enter the cochlea, they cause maximum displacement of the basilar membrane at the **helicotrema**, which is the apex or the farthest end of the cochlea. Hair cells in this region are specifically tuned to detect low-frequency sounds.","reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 675.","responses":[{"text":"Round window","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oval window","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helicotrema","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cochlear base","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9629,"text":"A person takes aspirin for chest pain. He feels a very strong bitter taste. Which nerve is responsible for carrying taste sensation from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue?","explanation":"The **facial nerve** (cranial nerve VII) is responsible for carrying taste sensation from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue. Taste buds on the tongue detect different tastes, such as sweet, sour, salty, and bitter, and transmit this information to the brain via specific cranial nerves.\r\n\r\nThe taste buds on the anterior two-thirds of the tongue are innervated by the **chorda tympani**, a branch of the facial nerve. The chorda tympani carries taste fibers from the taste buds to the brainstem, specifically the **solitary nucleus**. From there, taste information is further transmitted to the thalamus and eventually reaches the gustatory cortex in the brain, where the perception of taste occurs.\r\n\r\nIn the scenario described, the strong bitter taste experienced after taking aspirin indicates activation of the taste buds that detect bitterness. This sensation is conveyed by the facial nerve, highlighting its role in carrying taste sensation from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue.","reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 687.","responses":[{"text":"Vagus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoglossal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trigeminal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glossopharyngeal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9630,"text":"Which of the following is the most sensitive part of the eye?","explanation":"Among the options provided, the **fovea** is the most sensitive part of the eye. The fovea is a small depression located in the central region of the **macula** within the retina.\r\n\r\nThe retina is the innermost layer of the eye that contains specialized photoreceptor cells called **cones** and **rods**. These cells are responsible for detecting light and initiating the process of vision. The fovea is densely packed with cone cells and has a high concentration of **photoreceptors**, making it the area of highest visual acuity and sensitivity.\r\n\r\nThe fovea is specifically designed for detailed and central vision, enabling us to focus on objects with precision. It is responsible for sharp central vision, color perception, and the ability to discern fine details. When we direct our gaze towards an object, the light from that object falls directly onto the fovea, maximizing the visual information processed by the cones in that area.","reference":"Somilleda-Ventura SA, Ceballos-Reyes GM, Lima-Gómez V. Comparison of macular retinal sensitivity and its contribution to the foveal sensitivity between diabetic and non-diabetic patients with normal visual acuity. J Optom. 2019;12(3):180-185. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6612026/","responses":[{"text":"Macula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fovea","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Retina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Choroid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9631,"text":"A patient comes to the outpatient department with complaints of dryness of nose and palate. Which ganglion must be damaged?","explanation":"When a patient presents with symptoms of dryness in the nose and palate, the **pterygopalatine ganglion** is a likely site of damage. The pterygopalatine ganglion, also known as the **sphenopalatine ganglion**, is a parasympathetic ganglion located in the pterygopalatine fossa.\r\n\r\nThe pterygopalatine ganglion is responsible for innervating various structures in the head and neck, including the nasal mucosa and the palatal glands. It receives preganglionic parasympathetic fibers from the facial nerve (CN VII) via the **greater petrosal nerve** and the **nerve of the pterygoid canal**.\r\n\r\nThe postganglionic parasympathetic fibers from the pterygopalatine ganglion travel to the nasal mucosa, where they stimulate **mucous glands** and promote the secretion of mucus. Additionally, these fibers also innervate the **palatal glands**, which are responsible for producing saliva and maintaining moisture in the palate.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 986.","responses":[{"text":"Otic ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nodose ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ciliary ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterygopalatine ganglion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9632,"text":"Which type of gland is the gland of Zeis?","explanation":"The **gland of Zeis** is a type of **modified sebaceous gland** located in the eyelids. It is named after the Swiss anatomist Johann Gottfried Zeis, who first described these glands.\r\n\r\nSebaceous glands are typically found throughout the body and are responsible for producing sebum, an oily substance that helps lubricate and protect the skin and hair. In the case of the gland of Zeis, it is specifically associated with the eyelashes.\r\n\r\nThe gland of Zeis is located in the **dermis** of the eyelid, near the base of the eyelash follicle. Its primary function is to secrete **sebum** onto the base of the eyelash, helping to keep the eyelash and the surrounding skin moisturized and lubricated.\r\n\r\nThe secretion of sebum from the gland of Zeis helps prevent the eyelashes from becoming dry and brittle. It also plays a role in preventing the eyelashes from sticking together and promotes their flexibility.","reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 252.","responses":[{"text":"Modified sweat glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucus glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modified sebaceous glands","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mebomian glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modified lacrimal glands","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9633,"text":"Which part of the eye continues to grow throughout the lifetime?","explanation":"Among the structures listed, the **lens** is part of the eye that continues to grow throughout a person's lifetime.\r\n\r\nThe lens is a transparent structure located behind the iris. Its main function is to focus light onto the retina, allowing for clear vision. During development, the lens grows and achieves its mature size. However, unlike other parts of the eye, the lens continues to grow slowly throughout life. This growth is known as **lenticular growth** or **lenticular hypertrophy**.\r\n\r\nThe growth of the lens is a gradual process that occurs through the addition of new lens fibers in the central region of the lens. These new fibers are continuously produced by the **lens epithelial cells** located at the equator of the lens. As new fibers are added, the lens becomes thicker and more convex.\r\n\r\nThe ongoing growth of the lens contributes to changes in its shape and refractive power, which can affect vision and the need for corrective lenses as individuals age.","reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 252.","responses":[{"text":"Retina","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lens","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Choroid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cornea","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9635,"text":"Optic vesicles are out pocketings formed by which of the following structures?","explanation":"Optic vesicles are outpocketings formed by the **diencephalon** during embryonic development.\r\n\r\nThe development of the eye begins with the formation of the optic vesicles, which are evaginations or outpocketings from the developing brain. The optic vesicles arise from the **diencephalon**, specifically the **optic sulci**, which are bilateral grooves in the embryonic brain.\r\n\r\nAs the optic vesicles grow, they invaginate to form a double-layered optic cup. The inner layer of the optic cup gives rise to the **retina**, while the outer layer gives rise to the **pigmented epithelium** of the eye.\r\n\r\nThe optic vesicles also give rise to other structures involved in vision, including the **optic stalk** and the **optic nerve**. The optic nerve connects the retina to the brain, allowing for the transmission of visual information.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 419.","responses":[{"text":"Rhombencephalon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diencephalon","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesencephalon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prosencephalon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Telencephalon","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9636,"text":"The intermaxillary segment is formed by fusion of which of the following?","explanation":"The **intermaxillary segment** is formed by the fusion of the **two medial nasal prominences** during embryonic development.\r\n\r\nDuring early development, the face undergoes a complex process of fusion and growth from various facial prominences. The medial nasal prominences are paired structures located at the midline of the developing face. They contribute to the formation of the upper lip, philtrum (vertical groove on the upper lip), and primary palate.\r\n\r\nThe fusion of the two medial nasal prominences gives rise to the intermaxillary segment, also known as the **premaxilla**. This segment contains the primary incisors and contributes to the formation of the philtrum. The intermaxillary segment eventually fuses with the two maxillary prominences, which form the lateral parts of the upper lip.","reference":"(1) Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 301.\r\n\r\n\r\n(2) Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 178.","responses":[{"text":"Maxillary and nasal prominences","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial and lateral nasal prominences","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Two lateral nasal prominences","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Two medial nasal prominences","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9637,"text":"Which of the following structures is derived from the 1st pharyngeal arch?","explanation":"The **malleus** is derived from the **1st pharyngeal arch** during embryonic development.\r\n\r\nThe pharyngeal arches are a series of structures that form in the developing embryo and give rise to various anatomical components of the head and neck. The first pharyngeal arch, also known as the mandibular arch, plays a crucial role in the formation of several important structures.\r\n\r\nOne of the derivatives of the first pharyngeal arch is the malleus, which is one of the three ossicles of the middle ear. The malleus develops from the cartilaginous structure within the first pharyngeal arch and undergoes ossification to form the bony structure that participates in sound transmission.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 160.","responses":[{"text":"Greater cornu of hyoid bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stylohyoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccinator","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malleus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9638,"text":"An infant has a cleft on the right side of the palate behind the incisive foramen. The surgeon identifies it as which of the following?","explanation":"During embryonic development, the palate forms in two stages: the primary palate formation and the secondary palate formation. The primary palate is formed by the fusion of the medial nasal prominences, while the secondary palate is formed by the fusion of the two lateral palatal shelves.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the cleft is located behind the incisive foramen, which is a landmark separating the primary and secondary palates. Since the cleft is specifically on the right side of the palate and occurs behind the incisive foramen, it is classified as a **unilateral cleft of the posterior (secondary) palate**.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 187.","responses":[{"text":"Bilateral cleft of primary palate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unilateral cleft of primary and posterior palate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unilateral cleft of primary palate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bilateral cleft of secondary palate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unilateral cleft of posterior (secondary) palate","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9639,"text":"Which of the following is the area of epistaxis in the nose?","explanation":"The **area of epistaxis**, or nosebleed, commonly occurs in a specific region called **Little's area**.\r\n\r\nLittle's area, also known as **Kiesselbach's plexus**, is located in the anterior part of the nasal septum. It is a highly vascular area formed by the convergence of several blood vessels, including the anterior ethmoidal artery (a branch of the ophthalmic artery), the superior labial artery (a branch of the facial artery), and the septal branch of the sphenopalatine artery (a branch of the maxillary artery). \r\n\r\nDue to the rich blood supply in this area, it is prone to bleeding, and nosebleeds originating from Little's area are quite common. The proximity of these blood vessels to the surface of the nasal septum makes them susceptible to trauma, irritation, or dryness, leading to bleeding.","reference":"Tabassom A, Cho JJ. Epistaxis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 25, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK435997/","responses":[{"text":"Entire nasal septum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Floor of nasal cavity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Little's area","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Roof of nasal cavity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral wall of nasal cavity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9640,"text":"Which of the following structures divides the posterior triangle of the neck into two parts?","explanation":"The **inferior belly of the omohyoid** muscle divides the posterior triangle of the neck into two parts.\r\n\r\nThe posterior triangle of the neck is a region located between the sternocleidomastoid muscle, the trapezius muscle, and the clavicle. It is further divided into two smaller triangles, the occipital triangle (above the inferior belly of the omohyoid) and the subclavian triangle (below the inferior belly of the omohyoid).\r\n\r\nThe omohyoid muscle is a strap-like muscle that runs diagonally across the neck. It has two bellies, the superior belly and the inferior belly. The inferior belly of the omohyoid crosses horizontally through the posterior triangle, dividing it into its two parts.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1013.","responses":[{"text":"Posterior belly of digastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior belly of omohyoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior belly of digastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior belly of omohyoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater cornu of hyoid bone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9641,"text":"Which of the following structures forms the superior border of the digastric triangle?","explanation":"The **mandible** forms the superior border of the digastric triangle.\r\n\r\nThe digastric triangle is a region in the anterior neck bounded by the midline of the neck, the posterior belly of the digastric muscle, and the inferior border of the mandible. It contains various structures, including the submandibular gland and lymph nodes.\r\n\r\nThe mandible, or lower jawbone, is a U-shaped bone that forms the framework of the lower part of the face. Its superior border acts as the superior boundary of the digastric triangle. The anterior belly of the digastric muscle arises from the digastric fossa on the inner surface of the mandible and extends posteriorly to attach to the intermediate tendon.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 995.","responses":[{"text":"Inferior belly of omohyoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyoid bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior belly of digastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sternocleidomastoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mandible","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9642,"text":"Which of the following structures is involved in forming the lateral border of the muscular triangle?","explanation":"The **superior belly of the omohyoid muscle** is involved in forming the lateral border of the muscular triangle.\r\n\r\nThe muscular triangle is a region in the anterior neck bounded by the midline of the neck, the superior belly of the omohyoid muscle, and the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle. It contains various structures, including the infrahyoid muscles, thyroid gland, and larynx.\r\n\r\nThe superior belly of the omohyoid muscle is one of the infrahyoid muscles. It arises from the intermediate tendon and runs superiorly and laterally to insert on the hyoid bone. It forms the lateral border of the muscular triangle and plays a role in stabilizing the hyoid bone and depresses it during swallowing and speaking.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 995.","responses":[{"text":"Hyoid bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior belly of omohyoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Midline of the neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mandible","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior belly of omohyoid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9643,"text":"Which of the following muscles is involved in shrugging of shoulders?","explanation":"The **trapezius muscle** is involved in the shrugging of shoulders.\r\n\r\nThe trapezius is a large muscle located in the upper back and neck region. It has a trapezoid shape, hence its name. This muscle plays a key role in various movements of the shoulder girdle, including elevation, retraction, and depression of the scapulae.\r\n\r\nDuring shoulder shrugging, the trapezius muscle contracts to elevate the scapulae and bring the shoulders closer to the ears. This movement is commonly associated with expressing uncertainty, doubt, or indifference.\r\n\r\nThe trapezius muscle has three parts: the superior, middle, and inferior fibers. The superior fibers primarily elevate the scapulae, while the middle and inferior fibers retract and depress the scapulae, respectively. The combined action of these fibers allows for coordinated movement during shoulder shrugging.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 703.","responses":[{"text":"Deltoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Teres major/minor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectoralis major/minor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supraspinatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trapezius","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9648,"text":"A chef adds too much salt to the soup by mistake. Which of the following is the appropriate area of the tongue which detects salty taste?","explanation":"The appropriate area of the tongue that detects salty taste is the **anterior U-shaped area of the tongue**.\r\n\r\nSalty taste is one of the five basic tastes, and it is primarily detected by taste buds located on the anterior part of the tongue. These taste buds contain specialized receptors called sodium ion channels, which are responsive to the presence of sodium ions in food.\r\n\r\nThe distribution of taste buds responsible for detecting salty taste is more prominent in the anterior U-shaped area of the tongue. This area includes the fungiform papillae, which are small, mushroom-shaped structures on the tip and sides of the tongue. The taste buds on these papillae are particularly sensitive to salty stimuli.\r\n\r\nWhile some degree of salt taste can be detected in other areas of the tongue, the anterior U-shaped area is more specialized in detecting and discriminating salty flavors.","reference":"Head and neck module, Physiology lecture slides, Topic: Sense of taste, Sub-topic: Taste receptors distribution.","responses":[{"text":"Almost entire area of tongue ventrally","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Back of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior U-shaped area of the tongue","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sides of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tip of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9649,"text":"A person eats something, which is so bitter that he has to puke it out. Which of the following is the appropriate area of the tongue which detects bitter taste?","explanation":"The appropriate area of the tongue that detects bitter taste is the **back of the tongue**.\r\n\r\nBitter taste is one of the five basic tastes, and it is often associated with substances that can be potentially harmful or toxic. The taste buds located at the back of the tongue, specifically on the circumvallate papillae, are particularly sensitive to bitter taste. These taste buds contain specialized receptors called bitter receptors that detect the presence of bitter compounds.\r\n\r\nWhile bitter taste can be detected in other areas of the tongue to some extent, the concentration of taste buds on the back of the tongue makes it more responsive to bitter stimuli. This sensitivity to bitter taste helps to protect us from consuming harmful substances.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that different taste sensations can be detected in various regions of the tongue, contributing to our overall perception of flavor.","reference":"Head and neck module, Physiology lecture slides, Topic: Sense of taste, Sub-topic: Taste receptors distribution.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior U-shaped area of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Back of the tongue","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Almost entire area of tongue ventrally","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tip of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sides of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9650,"text":"A person eats something and finds it to have a delicious taste called umami. Which of the following is the appropriate area of the tongue which detects umami taste?","explanation":"The appropriate area of the tongue that detects umami taste is **almost the entire area of the tongue ventrally**.\r\n\r\n**Umami** is one of the five basic tastes, and it is often described as a savory or meaty flavor. It is commonly detected in foods rich in glutamate, such as meat, cheese, and mushrooms. The taste buds on the ventral surface of the tongue are particularly sensitive to umami taste. These taste buds contain specialized receptors called umami receptors that detect the presence of glutamate and certain other amino acids.\r\n\r\nWhile umami taste can be detected throughout the ventral surface of the tongue, it is worth noting that other taste sensations, such as sweet, sour, salty, and bitter, are also detected in this region. The distribution of taste buds across the tongue ensures that different tastes can be detected and contribute to our overall perception of flavor.","reference":"Head and neck module, Physiology lecture slides, Topic: Sense of taste, Sub-topic: Taste receptors distribution.","responses":[{"text":"Sides of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Almost entire area of tongue ventrally","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tip of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Back of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior U-shaped area of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9651,"text":"A man plans to lose weight so he cuts off calories and makes a salad for himself. Upon tasting it, he finds out that there is too much lemon in it. Which of the following is the appropriate area of the tongue which detects sour taste?","explanation":"The appropriate area of the tongue that detects sour taste is the **sides of the tongue**.\r\n\r\nWhen the man tastes the salad with excessive lemon, the taste buds on the sides of his tongue respond to the presence of sour compounds, such as citric acid. These taste buds are specifically tuned to detect sour tastes. The sour taste sensation is generated when these taste buds are stimulated by the acidic substances in the food.\r\n\r\nThe tongue is divided into different regions, and taste buds for different tastes are distributed across these regions. While the sides of the tongue are particularly sensitive to sour tastes, other areas of the tongue, such as the tip and the back, also contribute to the overall perception of sourness.","reference":"Head and neck module, Physiology lecture slides, Topic: Sense of taste, Sub-topic: Taste receptors distribution.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior U-shaped area of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Almost entire area of tongue ventrally","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tip of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sides of the tongue","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Back of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9652,"text":"A person eats something which is very sweet. Which of the following is the appropriate area of the tongue which detects sweet taste?","explanation":"**Tip of the tongue** is the appropriate area of the tongue that detects sweet taste.\r\n\r\nThe tongue is responsible for detecting various tastes, including sweet, sour, salty, bitter, and umami. Different taste buds on the tongue are specialized for specific tastes. In the case of sweet taste, the taste buds located at the tip of the tongue play a prominent role. When a person eats something sweet, the taste buds on the tip of the tongue respond to the presence of sugar molecules, triggering a sweet taste sensation.","reference":"Head and neck module, Physiology lecture slides, Topic: Sense of taste, Sub-topic: Taste receptors distribution.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior U-shaped area of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Back of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tip of the tongue","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Almost entire area of tongue ventrally","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sides of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9653,"text":"Which of the following is true regarding the tympanic membrane?","explanation":"The **tympanic membrane**, also known as the eardrum, is a thin, cone-shaped structure that separates the external ear from the middle ear. It plays a crucial role in transmitting sound vibrations to the ossicles of the middle ear.\r\n\r\nDuring embryogenesis, the development of the middle ear structures involves contributions from the first and second pharyngeal arches. The **malleus and incus**, two of the three ossicles of the middle ear, **are derived from the first pharyngeal arch**. The malleus originates from the mesenchyme of the first arch's mandibular process, while the incus develops from the mesenchyme of the first arch's dorsal end. Together with the stapes, which is derived from the second arch, these ossicles form the auditory ossicular chain responsible for sound transmission.\r\n\r\nThe incorrect options can be addressed as follows:\r\n- Pars flaccida is the **area above the posterior malleolar fold**, not between the umbo of the malleus and the posterior malleolar fold.\r\n- The **footplate of the stapes attaches to the oval window**, which is the membrane-covered opening leading to the inner ear, not the tympanic membrane.\r\n- The tympanic membrane consists of **three layers**: the outer epithelial layer, the middle fibrous layer, and the inner mucosal layer, not two layers.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 945, 946.","responses":[{"text":"It consists of 2 layers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Footplate of stapes attaches to it","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malleus and incus are derived from first pharyngeal arch during embryogenesis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars flaccida is the area between the umbo of malleus and the posterior malleolar fold","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9654,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding mastoid air cells and mastoid antrum?","explanation":"The **mastoid antrum**, which is a cavity within the mastoid process of the temporal bone, is indeed separated from the middle cranial fossa by a thin bony plate called the **tegmen tympani**. \r\n\r\n- The canal for the facial nerve, known as the stylomastoid foramen, is located at the base of the skull and not below the aditus to the mastoid antrum.\r\n- The **suprameatal triangle** refers to a specific region on the lateral aspect of the temporal bone and is not directly associated with the mastoid process.\r\n- The mastoid air cells or antrum do not open on the posterior wall of the external ear.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 978.","responses":[{"text":"Suprameatal triangle is antero-inferior to the mastoid process","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mastoid air cells or antrum opens on the posterior wall of external ear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mastoid antrum is separated from middle cranial fossa by tegmen tympani","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The canal for facial nerve is below the aditus to the mastoid antrum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9657,"text":"A friend tells you a person's number. After a few minutes, you can not recall it. This is because it has been wiped out from which of the following?","explanation":"**Short-term memory** is a temporary storage system that allows for the retention and manipulation of information for a brief period, typically lasting from a few seconds up to a few minutes. It plays a crucial role in tasks such as remembering phone numbers, names, or other immediate information.\r\n\r\nThe process of transferring information from short-term memory to long-term memory involves complex neural mechanisms, including the consolidation of memories in the **hippocampus**. The hippocampus is involved in the encoding and initial storage of memories, but it is not the sole site for long-term memory storage. Once memories are consolidated, they are stored in various regions of the brain for long-term retrieval.\r\n\r\nWhile the hippocampus is critical for memory formation, the inability to recall a number after a few minutes does not necessarily imply damage to the hippocampus. It is more indicative of the limitations of short-term memory capacity and the temporary nature of information stored in this system.","reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 746.","responses":[{"text":"Implicit memory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hippocampus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Short-term memory","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Long-term memory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Episodic memory","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9658,"text":"Which of the following is true about the canal of Schlemm?","explanation":"The **canal of Schlemm**, also known as the **scleral venous sinus**, is an important structure located in the anterior chamber of the eye. It plays a crucial role in regulating the outflow of aqueous humor, which is important for maintaining intraocular pressure. \r\n\r\nOne of the true characteristics of the canal of Schlemm is that it is **lined by endothelium**. The endothelial cells form the inner lining of the canal and create a barrier between the aqueous humor and the surrounding tissues. The endothelium of the canal of Schlemm is composed of specialized cells that are responsible for the reabsorption of aqueous humor from the anterior chamber into the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nThe canal of Schlemm does not contain red blood cells, as it primarily serves as a drainage pathway for aqueous humor rather than blood. Additionally, it does not directly communicate with the vitreous chamber, as the aqueous humor flows through the anterior chamber and exits the eye through the canal of Schlemm and the venous system.","reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 246.","responses":[{"text":"It contains red cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is lined by endothelium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It communicates with the vitreous chamber","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is lined by stratified squamous epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9659,"text":"11-cis retinal bound to a specific protein is classified as which of the following?","explanation":"**Visual pigments** are light-sensitive molecules found in the photoreceptor cells of the retina. They play a crucial role in the process of vision by absorbing light and initiating the signal transduction cascade that leads to the generation of electrical signals in the retina.\r\n\r\nThe visual pigment molecule consists of a chromophore called **11-cis retinal**, which is derived from vitamin A, and an opsin protein. When light enters the eye and interacts with the visual pigment, it causes a conformational change in the retinal molecule, leading to the activation of the photoreceptor cell and the initiation of the visual signaling process.\r\n\r\nThe binding of 11-cis retinal to the opsin protein forms the functional visual pigment molecule, which is responsible for capturing light energy and initiating the phototransduction cascade. This process ultimately leads to the generation of electrical signals that are transmitted to the brain, where visual perception occurs.","reference":"Yoshizawa T. Photophysiological functions of visual pigments. Adv Biophys. 1984;17:5-67. \r\nhttps://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/6242325/","responses":[{"text":"Visual pigment","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinoid acid binding protein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Photo-transducer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intermediates","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10941,"text":"A 45-year-old male is diagnosed with a brain tumor that is pressing on the nerve that passes through a groove between pyramids and olives. Which of the following functions would be affected?","explanation":"If a brain tumor is pressing on the nerve that passes through the groove between the pyramids and olives, it is most likely affecting the **hypoglossal nerve** (cranial nerve XII). The hypoglossal nerve innervates the muscles of the tongue, both intrinsic and extrinsic.\r\n\r\nThe extrinsic muscles of the tongue are responsible for moving the tongue in different directions, such as protrusion, retraction, and side-to-side movement. The intrinsic muscles of the tongue are responsible for shaping the tongue during speech and swallowing.\r\n\r\nTherefore, if the tumor is compressing the hypoglossal nerve, it would result in the **paralysis of all the intrinsic muscles of the tongue**. This would lead to difficulty in articulating speech sounds correctly and impaired swallowing function.\r\n\r\nOther functions such as general sensations and taste on the tongue are primarily mediated by different cranial nerves. General sensations on the anterior two-thirds of the tongue are carried by the lingual nerve (branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve, V3), while taste on the posterior one-third of the tongue is mediated by the glossopharyngeal nerve (cranial nerve IX).","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 900, 901.","responses":[{"text":"Taste on the ipsilateral side of the anterior two thirds of a tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paralysis of all the extrinsic muscles of the tongue only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Taste on the ipsilateral side of the posterior one third of a tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"General sensations on the ipsilateral side of the anterior two thirds of a tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paralysis of all the intrinsic muscles of the tongue","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10942,"text":"Which of the following carries a sense of temperature directly from the anterior two-thirds of a tongue to the thalamus?","explanation":"The sense of temperature from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue is carried by the **spinal nucleus of the trigeminal nerve**. The trigeminal nerve, also known as cranial nerve V, is responsible for conveying sensory information from the face, including the tongue. The trigeminal nerve has three main branches: ophthalmic (V1), maxillary (V2), and mandibular (V3). The anterior two-thirds of the tongue is innervated by the lingual branch of the mandibular division (V3) of the trigeminal nerve.\r\n\r\nThe sensory information from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue is carried by the lingual nerve, a branch of the mandibular division. This lingual nerve contains sensory fibers that transmit information regarding taste, touch, and temperature from the tongue. These temperature sensations are relayed to the **spinal nucleus of the trigeminal nerve**, located in the medulla, which serves as the primary sensory nucleus for the trigeminal nerve.\r\n\r\nFrom the spinal nucleus of the trigeminal nerve, the temperature information is further transmitted to higher brain centers, including the **ventro postero lateral nucleus of the thalamus**, which is involved in processing and relaying sensory information to the cerebral cortex for conscious perception.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 333.","responses":[{"text":"Ventro postero lateral nucleus of thalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Main sensory nucleus of trigeminal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinal nucleus of trigeminal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Motor nucleus of trigeminal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesencephalic nucleus of trigeminal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10953,"text":"Which of the following cells of the brain detect pressure?","explanation":"**Osmoreceptors** are specialized sensory cells that are sensitive to changes in osmotic pressure. They are located primarily in the hypothalamus, specifically in the organum vasculosum of the lamina terminalis (OVLT) and the supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei.\r\n\r\nOsmoreceptors play a crucial role in regulating the body's water balance and maintaining osmotic homeostasis. When there is an increase in osmotic pressure, indicating a state of dehydration or high solute concentration, osmoreceptors are stimulated. This activation triggers a series of neuroendocrine responses that aim to conserve water and restore the body's fluid balance.\r\n\r\nThe detection of pressure by osmoreceptors is essential for maintaining proper fluid and electrolyte balance in the body. By responding to changes in osmotic pressure, osmoreceptors help regulate thirst, release antidiuretic hormone (ADH) from the posterior pituitary gland, and influence the sensation of thirst.","reference":"Koshy RM, Jamil RT. Physiology, osmoreceptors. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557510/","responses":[{"text":"Osmoreceptors","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ependymal cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Schwann cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oligodendrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Astrocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10982,"text":"A physician found an infection involving carotid sheath. Which of the following structures might be involved?","explanation":"The carotid sheath is a fibrous connective tissue structure that encloses and protects important structures in the neck, including the **common carotid artery, internal jugular vein, and vagus nerve**. The common carotid artery is a major blood vessel that supplies oxygenated blood to the head and neck. It is located within the carotid sheath, along with the internal jugular vein and vagus nerve.\r\n\r\nAn infection in the carotid sheath can potentially affect the common carotid artery, leading to inflammation and compromised blood flow. This can result in various clinical manifestations, including pain, swelling, and dysfunction of the affected artery. Prompt diagnosis and treatment are essential to prevent complications and preserve the arterial function.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 1002.","responses":[{"text":"Ansa cervicalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common carotid artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sympathetic chain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External jugular vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recurrent laryngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10983,"text":"Which of the following sets of bones have a major contribution to the nasal septum?","explanation":"The major contribution to the nasal septum is made by the **vomer** and the **perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone**.\r\n\r\nThe vomer is a thin, flat bone located in the midline of the nasal cavity. It extends vertically from the sphenoidal crest of the ethmoid bone to the maxillary crest of the palatine bone. The vomer forms the posterior and inferior part of the nasal septum.\r\n\r\nThe perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone is a thin, bony structure that projects inferiorly from the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone. It descends in the midline to join the vomer, forming the anterior part of the nasal septum.\r\n\r\nTogether, the vomer and the perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone provide the structural framework and support for the nasal septum. They help to divide the nasal cavity into two separate nasal passages, facilitating the airflow and separation of the respiratory and olfactory regions.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 1076.","responses":[{"text":"Lacrimal and sphenoidal bones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasal cartilage and nasal bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vomer and perpendicular plate of ethmoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior and superior nasal conchae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary and palatine bone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11041,"text":"Which of the following types of secretions are released into the troughs of circumvallate papillae?","explanation":"The secretions released into the troughs of circumvallate papillae, which are large papillae located at the back of the tongue, are **entirely serous** and originate from the **Von Ebner's glands**. \r\n\r\nVon Ebner's glands are minor salivary glands found at the base of the circumvallate papillae. They are serous glands that produce a watery and enzyme-rich secretion. These secretions play a crucial role in the taste perception and cleansing of the taste buds.\r\n\r\nThe serous secretions from Von Ebner's glands help to flush and renew the taste buds, allowing for the detection of new taste stimuli. They contribute to the removal of debris and the maintenance of taste sensitivity.","reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 171.","responses":[{"text":"Entirely mucous from gustatory glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Predominantly mucous from parotid gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Entirely serous from Von Ebner's gland","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Seromucous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Predominantly serous from parotid gland","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11043,"text":"Which of the following structures gives rise to the air-filled cavity present in the petrous part of the temporal bone?","explanation":"During embryonic development, the **first pharyngeal pouch** gives rise to several structures, including the middle ear cavity, auditory tube (Eustachian tube), and mastoid antrum and air cells.\r\n\r\nThe first pharyngeal pouch is an evagination of the endodermal lining of the pharynx, which extends laterally from the pharyngeal cavity. It ultimately gives rise to the epithelial lining of the middle ear cavity and the auditory tube.\r\n\r\nThe middle ear cavity, also known as the tympanic cavity, is an air-filled space located within the petrous part of the temporal bone. It houses the auditory ossicles (malleus, incus, and stapes) and communicates with the nasopharynx through the auditory tube.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 161.","responses":[{"text":"First pharyngeal arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Third pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Second pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fourth pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"First pharyngeal pouch","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11044,"text":"A 10-year-old boy came to the emergency department with a laceration on the tip of the chin which is bleeding. Which of the following arteries must be affected?","explanation":"The artery that must be affected in this scenario is the **mental artery**. The mental artery is a branch of the **inferior alveolar artery**, which itself is a branch of the **maxillary artery**. The mental artery supplies the chin and lower lip with blood.\r\n\r\nIn the case of a laceration on the tip of the chin that is bleeding, damage to the mental artery can result in significant bleeding from the site of the injury. The mental artery runs along the lower border of the mandible and enters the chin, where it provides blood supply to the soft tissues in that region.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 919.","responses":[{"text":"Infraorbital artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mental artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transverse facial artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11045,"text":"Which of the following lies posterior to the maxilla, inferior and deep to the zygomatic arch and ramus of the mandible?","explanation":"The **infratemporal fossa** lies posterior to the maxilla, inferior and deep to the zygomatic arch, and ramus of the mandible. It is an irregularly shaped space that contains various important structures involved in mastication and sensory innervation of the face.\r\n\r\nThe boundaries of the infratemporal fossa include the lateral pterygoid plate medially, the ramus of the mandible laterally, the zygomatic arch superiorly, and the medial pterygoid muscle posteriorly. The floor of the fossa is formed by the upper surface of the greater wing of the sphenoid bone.\r\n\r\nWithin the infratemporal fossa, one can find structures such as the medial and lateral pterygoid muscles, the maxillary artery, the pterygoid venous plexus, branches of the trigeminal nerve (V2 and V3), and the otic ganglion.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 981.","responses":[{"text":"Middle cranial fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mylohyoid groove","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Temporal fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterygopalatine fossa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infratemporal fossa","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11168,"text":"From which view can pterygopalatine fossa be seen best?","explanation":"The **pterygopalatine fossa** is best visualized from the **norma lateralis** view. The norma lateralis view provides a lateral perspective of the skull and allows for a clear visualization of the lateral structures, including the pterygopalatine fossa.\r\n\r\nIn the norma lateralis view, the lateral aspect of the skull is observed, allowing for the identification of key landmarks and structures related to the pterygopalatine fossa. These include the pterygoid process of the sphenoid bone, the maxillary sinus, the pterygomaxillary fissure, and the posterior aspect of the maxilla.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 992.","responses":[{"text":"Norma frontalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Norma occipitais","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Norma lateralis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Norma basalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Norma verticalis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11169,"text":"Xeropthalmia is defined as dryness of the eye. Damage to which of the following structures can cause xeropthalmia?","explanation":"Xerophthalmia, which refers to dryness of the eye, can be caused by damage to the **pterygopalatine ganglion**. The pterygopalatine ganglion is a parasympathetic ganglion located in the pterygopalatine fossa. It receives preganglionic parasympathetic fibers from the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) via the greater petrosal nerve and postganglionic parasympathetic fibers travel to various structures, including the lacrimal gland.\r\n\r\nThe parasympathetic fibers that pass through the pterygopalatine ganglion play a crucial role in regulating tear production. They stimulate the lacrimal gland to produce tears, which help keep the eye lubricated and prevent dryness. Damage to the pterygopalatine ganglion can disrupt the parasympathetic innervation of the lacrimal gland, leading to decreased tear production and resulting in xerophthalmia.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 998.","responses":[{"text":"Superior cervical ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Otic ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterygopalatine ganglion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ciliary ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11177,"text":"Which of the following gives rise to the pigment epithelium layer of an eye?","explanation":"The **outer layer of the optic cup** gives rise to the pigment epithelium layer of the eye. During embryonic development, the optic cup forms from the invagination of the optic vesicle. The outer layer of the optic cup differentiates into the **retinal pigment epithelium (RPE)**, which is a single layer of cells located adjacent to the neural retina. \r\n\r\nThe RPE plays a crucial role in supporting the function and health of the retina. It absorbs excess light, preventing scatter and reflection within the eye. It also provides nourishment to the photoreceptor cells of the retina and participates in the visual cycle by recycling visual pigments. Additionally, the RPE is involved in the production of growth factors and the maintenance of the blood-retinal barrier.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 421.","responses":[{"text":"Pars iris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Outer layer of optic cup","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inner layer of optic cup","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars ceca retinae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars ciliaris retinae","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11178,"text":"Which of the following muscles would be affected in case the trochlear nerve gets damaged?","explanation":"Damage to the **trochlear nerve (CN IV)** would result in weakness or paralysis of the **superior oblique muscle**. The trochlear nerve is responsible for innervating the superior oblique muscle, which is one of the extraocular muscles involved in eye movement.\r\n\r\nThe superior oblique muscle is responsible for downward and inward rotation of the eye. It plays a crucial role in mediating vertical and rotational movements of the eye, particularly when looking downward or in a medial direction.\r\n\r\nWhen the trochlear nerve is damaged, the affected individual may experience difficulty in moving the affected eye downward and inward. This can result in vertical or diagonal diplopia (double vision) and a tilted or twisted appearance of objects.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that the trochlear nerve is the only cranial nerve that emerges from the dorsal surface of the brainstem, crosses over to the opposite side, and innervates a muscle on the contralateral side.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 937.","responses":[{"text":"Lateral rectus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior oblique muscle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial rectus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior rectus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior oblique muscle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11179,"text":"Which of the following structures does not pass through the internal acoustic meatus?","explanation":"The **glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX)** does not pass through the **internal acoustic meatus**. The internal acoustic meatus is a bony canal located in the petrous part of the temporal bone. It serves as a pathway for several important structures.\r\n\r\nThe structures that pass through the internal acoustic meatus include the vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII), specifically its vestibular and cochlear divisions, as well as the labyrinthine artery. The vestibular division carries sensory information related to balance and spatial orientation, while the cochlear division carries auditory information.\r\n\r\nHowever, the glossopharyngeal nerve does not pass through the internal acoustic meatus. It arises from the medulla oblongata and exits the posterior cranial fossa through the jugular foramen, along with the vagus nerve (CN X) and accessory nerve (CN XI). The glossopharyngeal nerve primarily innervates structures in the head and neck, including the tongue, pharynx, and parotid gland.","reference":"Panara K, Hoffer M. Anatomy, head and neck, ear internal auditory canal(Internal auditory meatus, internal acoustic canal). In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK544288/","responses":[{"text":"Glossopharyngeal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vestibular division of 8th cranial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cochlear division of 8th cranial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Labyrinthine artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11183,"text":"Which muscle must be affected if the upper eye lid is droopy (ptosis)?","explanation":"If the upper eyelid is droopy (ptosis), the muscle that is most likely affected is the **palpebral part of the orbicularis oculi** muscle. The orbicularis oculi is a circular muscle that surrounds the eye and is responsible for closing the eyelids. It consists of two parts: the orbital part and the palpebral part.\r\n\r\nThe palpebral part of the orbicularis oculi muscle is specifically responsible for controlling the movement and position of the eyelids. It helps to maintain eyelid closure and contributes to the normal resting tone of the upper eyelid. Dysfunction or weakness of this muscle can result in ptosis, causing the upper eyelid to droop.\r\n\r\nPtosis can have various causes, including neurological conditions, muscle weakness or damage, or problems with the nerves that innervate the muscles of the eyelids. It is important to evaluate the function of the orbicularis oculi muscle and its innervation to determine the underlying cause of ptosis.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 930.","responses":[{"text":"Orbital part of orbicularis oculi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palpebral part of orbicularis oculi","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior tarsus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial rectus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior rectus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11194,"text":"Ethmoidal bulla can be seen in the middle nasal meatus. Which of the following is related to ethmoidal bulla?","explanation":"The ethmoidal bulla is related to the **middle ethmoidal sinus**. The ethmoidal sinuses are air-filled spaces located within the ethmoid bone, situated between the eyes and medial to the orbits. The middle ethmoidal sinus is one of the three main subdivisions of the ethmoidal sinuses.\r\n\r\nThe ethmoidal bulla is a rounded prominence or bulge that arises from the lateral wall of the middle nasal meatus. It represents the most anterior and largest part of the middle ethmoidal sinus. The bulla helps to define the boundaries of the middle ethmoidal sinus and contributes to the drainage of its contents.\r\n\r\nThe ethmoidal bulla is an important landmark during nasal endoscopic procedures and sinus surgeries. Its position and size can vary among individuals, and it plays a role in determining the anatomy and drainage patterns of the middle ethmoidal sinus.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 1073.","responses":[{"text":"Maxillary sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Frontal sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior ethmoidal sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle ethmoidal sinus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior ethmoidal sinus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11197,"text":"Damage to which of the following structures can cause relative afferent pupillary defect (RAPD)?","explanation":"Damage to the **optic nerve** can cause a **relative afferent pupillary defect (RAPD)**, also known as **Marcus Gunn pupil**. RAPD is an abnormal response of the pupil to light stimuli, where there is a reduced pupillary constriction or even dilation in the affected eye compared to the unaffected eye.\r\n\r\nThe optic nerve carries visual information from the retina to the brain. When there is damage to the optic nerve, such as optic nerve compression or injury, it can result in impaired transmission of visual signals. As a result, the affected eye may exhibit a diminished pupillary response to light.\r\n\r\nTo test for RAPD, the swinging flashlight test is performed. In this test, a bright light is alternated between the two eyes, and the pupillary responses are observed. A relative afferent pupillary defect is indicated by a decreased pupillary constriction or dilation in response to light in the affected eye, while the unaffected eye shows a normal pupillary response.","reference":"Simakurthy S, Tripathy K. Marcus gunn pupil. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557675/","responses":[{"text":"Occulomoter nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Optic nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trochlear nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial temporal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abducent nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11198,"text":"Which type of secretion is produced by the glands at the tip of the tongue?","explanation":"The glands located at the tip of the tongue produce **seromucous** secretions. Seromucous glands are a type of mixed gland that produce a combination of serous and mucous components in their secretions.\r\n\r\nThe serous component of the secretion is produced by serous acinar cells and contains enzymes and proteins, while the mucous component is produced by mucous acinar cells and consists of mucins and glycoproteins. The combination of these two types of secretions gives rise to the seromucous composition.\r\n\r\nThe seromucous secretions from the glands at the tip of the tongue serve important functions in maintaining oral health and lubricating the oral cavity during speaking and swallowing. The serous component contains enzymes that aid in digestion and antimicrobial properties that help protect against oral infections. The mucous component provides lubrication and helps to moisten the oral surfaces.","reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 195.","responses":[{"text":"Purely mucous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"gel like secretions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Purely serous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Watery secretions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Seromucous","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11227,"text":"Why is the temporomandibular joint, a compound condylar variety, called an atypical synovial joint?","explanation":"The temporomandibular joint (TMJ) is referred to as an **atypical synovial joint** primarily because its articular surfaces are covered by **fibrocartilage** instead of the typical hyaline cartilage found in other synovial joints. The fibrocartilage provides a smooth and resilient surface for the articulation between the mandibular condyle and the temporal bone.\r\n\r\nUnlike typical synovial joints, the TMJ exhibits a **compound condylar** structure, allowing for both hinge-like and sliding movements. This unique combination of movements enables the jaw to perform functions such as opening, closing, and lateral movements during activities like chewing and speaking.\r\n\r\nAnother noteworthy feature of the TMJ is the **attachment of the lateral pterygoid muscle** to the articular capsule. This muscle plays a significant role in the movement and stability of the joint, contributing to the overall functionality of the TMJ.\r\n\r\nIn summary, the TMJ is considered atypical due to its specialized fibrocartilaginous articular surfaces, compound condylar structure, and the involvement of the lateral pterygoid muscle in its function.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 924.","responses":[{"text":"It is between temporal bone and mandible","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is highly moveable joint","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibers of lateral pterygoid is are attached directly to the articular capsule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The articular surface is covered by fibrocartilage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a highly moveable joint but has no synovial fluid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11271,"text":"Light can not pass from which of the following layers of the eye?","explanation":"The **sclera** is the tough, white outer layer of the eye that provides structural support and protection. It covers most of the eyeball, except for the anterior portion which is covered by the transparent cornea.\r\n\r\nThe sclera is composed of dense collagen fibers that give it its strength and rigidity. These collagen fibers are densely packed, making the sclera relatively opaque to light. As a result, light cannot pass through the sclera to reach the inner layers of the eye, including the retina where the photoreceptor cells are located.\r\n\r\nInstead, light enters the eye through the transparent cornea, which acts as the primary refractive surface. The cornea allows light to pass through and focuses it onto the lens, which further refracts the light onto the retina for visual perception.","reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 244.","responses":[{"text":"Aqueous humor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sclera","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitreous humor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pupil","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11286,"text":"Which of the following muscles would not be affected if the pharyngeal plexus, which lies deep to the middle constrictor gets damaged?","explanation":"The **stylopharyngeus muscle** is innervated by the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX), which is not part of the pharyngeal plexus.\r\n\r\nThe pharyngeal plexus is formed by branches of the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX), vagus nerve (CN X), and sympathetic fibers. It supplies motor innervation to the muscles of the pharynx, including the superior, middle, and inferior constrictor muscles, as well as the palatopharyngeus and salpingopharyngeus muscles.\r\n\r\nHowever, the stylopharyngeus muscle, which plays a role in elevating and widening the pharynx during swallowing and speech, receives its motor innervation directly from the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX), bypassing the pharyngeal plexus. Therefore, if the pharyngeal plexus is damaged, the function of the stylopharyngeus muscle would remain unaffected.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 1051.","responses":[{"text":"Superior constrictor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salpingopharyngeus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatopharyngeus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stylopharyngeus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle constrictor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11503,"text":"Which of the following terms is defined as the inability to see in the bright light?","explanation":"The term that is defined as the inability to see in bright light is **hemeralopia**, also known as **day blindness**. Hemeralopia is a visual disorder characterized by reduced vision or complete blindness in bright light conditions, while vision in dim light or darkness remains relatively normal.\r\n\r\nHemeralopia is typically caused by dysfunction or damage to the **cone cells** in the retina, which are responsible for color vision and visual acuity in bright light. The condition can be congenital or acquired and may result from various underlying causes such as vitamin A deficiency, certain genetic conditions, retinal degeneration, or certain medications.\r\n\r\nPatients with hemeralopia often experience discomfort, glare, and difficulty adapting to bright light environments. Their vision may improve or normalize in low light conditions, where the rod cells in the retina take over as the primary photoreceptors.","reference":"Ohba N, Ohba A. Nyctalopia and hemeralopia: the current usage trend in the literature. Br J Ophthalmol. 2006;90(12):1548-1549. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1857511","responses":[{"text":"Heteropia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinitis pigmentosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Xerophthalmia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemiplegia retinitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemeralopia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11504,"text":"Maximal movement is shown by which of the following joints when the head moves horizontally such as to say \"no\"?","explanation":"The **atlantoaxial joint** is formed by the articulation between the atlas (C1) and axis (C2) vertebrae.\r\n\r\nThe atlantoaxial joint allows for rotation of the head around its vertical axis. This movement is primarily carried out by the dens (odontoid process) of the axis, which acts as a pivot within the anterior arch of the atlas. The joint between the dens and the atlas, known as the **atlantoaxial joint**, allows for significant rotational movement.\r\n\r\nWhen we turn our head horizontally, the atlas (C1) rotates around the dens of the axis (C2), allowing for the movement of the head. This pivotal movement at the atlantoaxial joint provides the maximum range of motion for horizontal head movements.","reference":"Atlantoaxial joint. Kenhub. Accessed April 26, 2022. https://www.kenhub.com/en/library/anatomy/atlantoaxial-joint","responses":[{"text":"C8-T1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atlanto-occipital","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C2-C3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C3-C4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atlanto axial","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11505,"text":"A 7-year-old presents to the outpatient department with the complaint of difficulty in chewing and swallowing. He also complains of pain in the auricular region and external ear. After examination, the doctor finds that there is an inflammation of the parotid gland. Which of the following nerves must be irritated to cause this pain?","explanation":"The **auriculotemporal** nerve is a branch of the mandibular division (V3) of the trigeminal nerve. The parotid gland is innervated by the parasympathetic secretomotor fibers derived from the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) via the **otic ganglion**. However, the pain sensation in the region is mediated by the sensory fibers of the auriculotemporal nerve, which also carries the parasympathetic secretomotor fibers to the parotid gland.\r\n\r\nIrritation or inflammation of the parotid gland can result in the activation of the sensory fibers of the auriculotemporal nerve, leading to pain referred to the auricular region and external ear. This phenomenon is known as **referred pain**. The presence of difficulty in chewing and swallowing can be attributed to the enlargement and inflammation of the parotid gland, which may impede normal function.","reference":"Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur AMR. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer/Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins Health; 2014: 926.","responses":[{"text":"Maxillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingual nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Auriculotemporal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11506,"text":"Which of the following is an active metabolite of vitamin A present in the eye?","explanation":"The active metabolite of vitamin A present in the eye is **retinal**. Retinal is a crucial component of the visual cycle and plays a fundamental role in the process of vision. It is derived from the conversion of retinol, the primary form of vitamin A, in a series of enzymatic reactions.\r\n\r\nIn the retina, retinal combines with opsin, a protein found in the photoreceptor cells, to form visual pigments called **rhodopsin** (in rods) and **iodopsin** (in cones). These pigments are responsible for the absorption of light and the initiation of the visual signal transduction pathway.\r\n\r\nWhen light enters the eye and reaches the retina, it is absorbed by retinal, causing a conformational change in the visual pigment. This change triggers a series of events that eventually result in the generation of nerve impulses that are transmitted to the brain for visual perception.","reference":"Wilson M, Pandey S. Parotitis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560735/","responses":[{"text":"Retinal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta carotene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carotenoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinoic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11513,"text":"Dorsum of the tongue is lined by which epithelium?","explanation":"The dorsum (upper surface) of the tongue is lined by **stratified squamous partially keratinized** epithelium. The tongue is composed of different regions, each with its own specialized epithelium. The dorsum of the tongue, which is the visible surface, is covered by this type of epithelium.\r\n\r\nStratified squamous epithelium is a protective epithelium found in areas subjected to mechanical stress, such as the oral cavity. The term \"partially keratinized\" refers to the presence of keratin in the superficial layers of the epithelium. Keratin provides strength and durability to the tissue.\r\n\r\nThe stratified squamous partially keratinized epithelium on the dorsum of the tongue helps withstand the abrasion and friction caused by food and tongue movements during speech and mastication. It also contains taste buds, which play a crucial role in the perception of taste.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 170.","responses":[{"text":"Pseudostratified columnar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified columnar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous non-keratinized","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous keratinized","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous partially keratinized","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11732,"text":"Which of the following are the end products of hydrolysis of retinyl esters in intestinal mucosa?","explanation":"The hydrolysis of retinyl esters in the intestinal mucosa results in the formation of **retinol** and **free fatty acids**. Retinyl esters are storage forms of vitamin A found in dietary sources. In order for vitamin A to be absorbed and utilized by the body, these retinyl esters need to be hydrolyzed into their constituent parts.\r\n\r\nIn the intestinal mucosa, the enzyme *pancreatic triglyceride lipase* (PTL) plays a key role in the hydrolysis of retinyl esters. PTL breaks down the ester bond, releasing retinol and fatty acids. The retinol is then incorporated into *chylomicrons*, which are lipoprotein particles that transport dietary fats and fat-soluble vitamins.\r\n\r\nRetinol, the active form of vitamin A, is essential for various biological processes, including vision, embryonic development, and cellular differentiation. It serves as a precursor for the synthesis of other active forms of vitamin A, such as retinal and retinoic acid, which have specific roles in vision and gene regulation, respectively.","reference":"Retinol ester - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed May 5, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/retinol-ester","responses":[{"text":"Retinal and retinol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinoic acid and free fatty acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinal and free fatty acids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinoic acid and retinol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinol and free fatty acids","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11733,"text":"Which of the following muscles is attached to the articular disc of the temporomandibular joint?","explanation":"The **lateral pterygoid muscle** is attached to the articular disc of the temporomandibular joint (TMJ). The TMJ is a synovial joint that allows for the movement of the mandible during activities such as chewing, speaking, and yawning.\r\n\r\nThe lateral pterygoid muscle has two heads: the upper head and the lower head. The upper head originates from the infratemporal surface of the greater wing of the sphenoid bone, while the lower head originates from the lateral surface of the lateral pterygoid plate of the sphenoid bone. Both heads converge and insert onto the neck of the condylar process of the mandible.\r\n\r\nThe articular disc is a fibrocartilaginous structure located between the mandibular condyle and the temporal bone. It divides the TMJ into two compartments: an upper compartment and a lower compartment. The upper compartment allows for gliding and rotational movements, while the lower compartment permits hinging movements of the mandible.\r\n\r\nThe attachment of the lateral pterygoid muscle to the articular disc plays a crucial role in the movement and stabilization of the TMJ. Contraction of the lateral pterygoid muscle assists in the forward and side-to-side movements of the mandible during chewing and speaking.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 931.","responses":[{"text":"Medial pterygoid muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Temporalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral pterygoid muscle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Massetor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccinator","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11734,"text":"Which of the following muscles are involved in the formation of transverse and vertical wrinkles on the forehead?","explanation":"The **frontalis** muscle is a broad, thin muscle that covers the frontal bone of the skull. It extends from the forehead to the eyebrows and is responsible for raising the eyebrows and forming horizontal wrinkles across the forehead when contracted. It is innervated by the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII).\r\n\r\nThe **corrugator supercilii** muscle is a small, narrow muscle located deep to the frontalis muscle. It is positioned above the medial part of the eyebrow and is responsible for drawing the eyebrows medially and downward, forming vertical wrinkles between the eyebrows when contracted. It is also innervated by the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII).\r\n\r\nThe coordinated action of the frontalis and corrugator supercilii muscles allows for a wide range of facial expressions, including raising the eyebrows, furrowing the forehead, and expressing emotions such as surprise or concern.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 853, 855, 856.","responses":[{"text":"Corrugator supercilii and orbicularis oculi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Frontalis and mentalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Frontalis and orbicularis oculi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corrugator supercilii and mentalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Frontalis and corrugator supercilii","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11735,"text":"Which of the following contains receptors to detect centrifugal acceleration in order to determine angular acceleration?","explanation":"The **semicircular canals** are part of the inner ear and play a crucial role in the vestibular system, which is responsible for maintaining balance and detecting head movements.\r\n\r\nThe semicircular canals are oriented in different planes (anterior, posterior, and horizontal) and are filled with fluid called endolymph. When the head undergoes rotational movements, the endolymph within the canals also moves, causing displacement of specialized sensory hair cells located within the ampullae at the base of each canal.\r\n\r\nThe sensory hair cells within the ampullae are equipped with cilia, known as stereocilia, which are embedded in a gelatinous structure called the cupula. When the head rotates, the movement of the endolymph exerts forces on the cupula, bending the stereocilia and triggering sensory signals that are transmitted to the brain via the vestibulocochlear nerve (cranial nerve VIII).\r\n\r\nThus, the semicircular canals, with their specialized sensory apparatus, are specifically designed to detect and respond to angular acceleration, providing essential information for maintaining balance and coordinating movements.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 706.","responses":[{"text":"Cochlea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vestibule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saccule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Utricle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Semicircular canals","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11736,"text":"Which wall of the middle ear contains an opening for the pharyngotympanic tube?","explanation":"The **anterior wall** of the middle ear contains an opening for the **pharyngotympanic tube**, also known as the Eustachian tube. This tube connects the middle ear to the nasopharynx, allowing for equalization of pressure between the middle ear and the atmosphere.\r\n\r\nThe pharyngotympanic tube serves an important function in regulating pressure in the middle ear. It opens during swallowing, yawning, or chewing, allowing air to enter or exit the middle ear space. This equalizes the pressure between the middle ear and the external environment, preventing discomfort or damage to the eardrum.\r\n\r\nThe opening of the pharyngotympanic tube is located in the anterior wall of the middle ear, close to the anterior tympanic membrane. It is lined with mucous membrane and is surrounded by a small cartilaginous structure called the torus tubarius.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 947.","responses":[{"text":"Posterior wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Roof","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior wall","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral wall","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11737,"text":"Which of the following triangles of neck contains chemoreceptors?","explanation":"The **carotid triangle** is located in the anterior region of the neck, bounded by the posterior belly of the digastric muscle, the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, and the superior belly of the omohyoid muscle.\r\n\r\nWithin the carotid triangle, there are clusters of chemoreceptor cells called **carotid bodies**. These specialized cells are sensitive to changes in blood chemistry, particularly the levels of oxygen, carbon dioxide, and pH. They play a crucial role in regulating respiratory function and maintaining homeostasis.\r\n\r\nWhen there is a decrease in blood oxygen levels or an increase in carbon dioxide levels or acidity, the carotid bodies are stimulated. They send signals to the brainstem, which then initiates corrective responses such as increased ventilation to restore oxygen levels and eliminate carbon dioxide.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 999, 1009, 1067.","responses":[{"text":"Muscular triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carotid triangle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mental triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submental triangle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11738,"text":"Third-order neurons of the taste pathway terminate at which of the following areas of the brain?","explanation":"Third-order neurons of the taste pathway terminate at the **opercular insular area** of the brain. This area, also known as the gustatory cortex, is located in the insular lobe of the cerebral cortex.\r\n\r\nThe taste pathway involves a series of three neurons: the first-order, second-order, and third-order neurons. The first-order neurons originate in the taste buds located on the tongue and transmit signals to the brainstem. The second-order neurons ascend from the brainstem to the thalamus, specifically the ventral posteromedial nucleus (VPM). From there, the third-order neurons project to the opercular insular area.\r\n\r\nThe opercular insular area is responsible for the conscious perception, discrimination, and analysis of taste sensations. It plays a crucial role in interpreting and integrating taste information, allowing us to differentiate between different tastes such as sweet, sour, bitter, salty, and umami.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 678.","responses":[{"text":"Broadman's area 6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Broadman's area 22","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Broca's area","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opercular insular area","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Broadman's area 17","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11739,"text":"A soldier lost his sense of hearing due to exposure to loud sounds. Damage to which of the following organs can result in hearing loss?","explanation":"Hearing loss resulting from exposure to loud sounds is often associated with damage to the **inner hair cells** of the cochlea. The cochlea is the spiral-shaped organ of the inner ear responsible for converting sound vibrations into electrical signals that can be interpreted by the brain.\r\n\r\nThe inner hair cells play a crucial role in the process of auditory transduction. When sound waves enter the cochlea, they cause vibrations in the fluid-filled chambers. These vibrations stimulate the hair cells, which convert the mechanical energy into electrical signals. The electrical signals are then transmitted to the auditory nerve and eventually to the brain for interpretation.\r\n\r\nDamage to the inner hair cells can occur due to prolonged or intense exposure to loud sounds, leading to **sensorineural hearing loss**. This type of hearing loss is characterized by a reduction in the ability to detect and understand sounds, particularly in the higher frequency range.","reference":"Kurabi A, Keithley EM, Housley GD, Ryan AF, Wong ACY. Cellular mechanisms of noise-induced hearing loss. Hearing Research. Published June 2017. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27916698/","responses":[{"text":"Cochlea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inner hair cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Saccule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Utricle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vestibule","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11795,"text":"Which of the following suprahyoid muscles is supplied by C1 fibers along the hypoglossal nerve?","explanation":"The **suprahyoid muscles** are a group of muscles located above the hyoid bone in the neck. They play a role in various functions such as swallowing, speaking, and raising the hyoid bone during swallowing. The hypoglossal nerve (cranial nerve XII) provides motor innervation to several muscles in the neck, including the geniohyoid muscle.\r\n\r\nAmong the options provided, the **geniohyoid muscle** receives innervation from the C1 fibers that travel along the hypoglossal nerve. The geniohyoid muscle is a thin muscle that runs from the mental spine of the mandible to the hyoid bone. It helps to depress and stabilize the hyoid bone.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 996.","responses":[{"text":"Stylohyoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyrohyoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Digastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Geniohyoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stylothyroid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11796,"text":"Which of the following nerves does not pass through the jugular foramen?","explanation":"The **jugular foramen** is an important bony canal located at the base of the skull, at the junction between the petrous part of the temporal bone and the occipital bone. It serves as a passage for several important nerves and blood vessels. \r\n\r\nAmong the options provided, the **spinal part of the accessory nerve** does not pass through the jugular foramen. The accessory nerve, also known as cranial nerve XI, has both cranial and spinal components. The cranial part of the accessory nerve does pass through the jugular foramen along with the **glossopharyngeal nerve**, **vagus nerve**, and the **cranial part of the accessory nerve**. However, the spinal part of the accessory nerve arises from the upper cervical spinal cord and does not pass through the jugular foramen. Instead, it enters the skull through the foramen magnum.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 842, 1067, 1085.","responses":[{"text":"Glossopharyngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinal part of accessory nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagus nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nerve to stylopharyngeus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cranial part of accessory nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11797,"text":"Which of the following is correct about the nerve that is responsible for the physiological peristaltic movements of the gastrointestinal tract?","explanation":"The nerve that is responsible for the physiological peristaltic movements of the gastrointestinal tract is the **vagus nerve**. It is also known as the **cranial nerve X**. The vagus nerve originates from the **medulla oblongata**, which is located in the brainstem. \r\n\r\nThe vagus nerve has both **sensory and motor functions**. Its motor fibers innervate the smooth muscles of the gastrointestinal tract, including the esophagus, stomach, and intestines. These motor fibers are responsible for coordinating the peristaltic movements that propel food along the digestive system.\r\n\r\nThe vagus nerve also provides parasympathetic innervation to various organs in the thoracic and abdominal cavities, including the heart, lungs, liver, and pancreas. It helps regulate various physiological processes, including digestion, heart rate, and respiratory function.\r\n\r\nThe statement that the vagus nerve is joined by the **cranial part of the accessory nerve** is correct. The accessory nerve, also known as cranial nerve XI, contributes some fibers that join the vagus nerve in the neck region.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 842, 997, 1014, 1067, 1084.","responses":[{"text":"Originates from pons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Does not give cardiac branches in the neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exits skull through foramen magnum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Present outside the carotid sheath","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Joined by cranial part of accessory nerve","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11798,"text":"Which of the following regions has the most abundant distribution of fungiform papillae?","explanation":"The **tip of the tongue** is the region that has the most abundant distribution of **fungiform papillae**. Fungiform papillae are mushroom-shaped papillae found on the surface of the tongue. They are scattered throughout the tongue but are particularly concentrated at the tip.\r\n\r\nFungiform papillae are important for taste sensation as they contain taste buds, which are responsible for detecting different tastes such as sweet, sour, salty, and bitter. The abundance of fungiform papillae at the tip of the tongue allows for a higher density of taste buds in this region, increasing the sensitivity to taste stimuli.\r\n\r\nThe distribution of fungiform papillae across different regions of the tongue is not uniform. While the tip of the tongue has a high concentration of fungiform papillae, the posterior regions, such as the back of the tongue, have fewer fungiform papillae and are primarily covered by a different type of papillae called circumvallate papillae.","reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 171.","responses":[{"text":"Sides of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsum of tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior 2/3rd of a tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Back of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tip of the tongue","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11799,"text":"Which of the following correctly describes the cause of the coloboma?","explanation":"A **coloboma** refers to a congenital malformation characterized by a gap or cleft in a specific structure of the eye. The most common cause of coloboma is the **failure of the choroidal fissure to close** during embryonic development.\r\n\r\nDuring eye development, the choroidal fissure is a transient invagination in the optic cup, which eventually closes to form the normal anatomical structures of the eye. If the closure of the choroidal fissure is incomplete, it results in a coloboma.\r\n\r\nThe coloboma can affect various structures of the eye, including the iris, retina, choroid, and optic disc. The location and size of the coloboma determine the extent of visual impairment or other associated ocular abnormalities.\r\n\r\nThe failure of the choroidal fissure to close properly during embryogenesis disrupts the normal development of these ocular structures, leading to the characteristic coloboma appearance.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 919.","responses":[{"text":"Abnormal development of optic cup","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Failure of optic cup to close","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Failure of lens vesicle to close","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Failure of choroidal fissure to close","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Failure of separation of eyelids","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11800,"text":"Which of the following correctly describes the function of the myenteric plexus in causing the peristaltic movements of the gut?","explanation":"The **myenteric plexus** plays a crucial role in coordinating the peristaltic movements of the gut. It is a network of nerve fibers located between the circular and longitudinal muscle layers of the gastrointestinal tract.\r\n\r\nPeristalsis is the coordinated contraction and relaxation of these muscle layers that propels the bolus of food through the digestive system. The myenteric plexus is responsible for **stimulating the circular muscles above the bolus**.\r\n\r\nWhen the bolus of food enters a segment of the gut, the myenteric plexus initiates contraction of the circular muscles proximal to the bolus. This contraction narrows the lumen of the gut, propelling the bolus forward. At the same time, the myenteric plexus inhibits the circular muscles distal to the bolus, allowing relaxation and dilation of the gut, preparing it for the arrival of the bolus.\r\n\r\nThis coordinated action of the myenteric plexus ensures the forward movement of the bolus through the gastrointestinal tract, facilitating digestion and absorption of nutrients.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 750.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibiting circular muscle below the bolus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stimulating circular muscles above the bolus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibiting longitudinal muscles below the bolus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibiting vagus nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibiting circular muscle above the bolus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11801,"text":"Which of the following nerves supplies the anterior aspect of the external auditory meatus?","explanation":"The **auriculotemporal nerve** is a branch of the mandibular division (V3) of the trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V). It carries sensory fibers that innervate the skin of the external acoustic meatus, as well as the skin of the external ear, the temporal region, and the lateral scalp. \r\n\r\nThe anterior aspect of the external auditory meatus refers to the front portion or opening of the ear canal. The auriculotemporal nerve provides sensory innervation to this area, allowing for the perception of touch, pain, and temperature sensations.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that while the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) supplies the muscles of the face, it does not directly supply sensory innervation to the external auditory meatus.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 975.","responses":[{"text":"Greater auricular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagus nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Auriculotemporal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glossopharyngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11802,"text":"Which of the following structures is damaged if norma lateralis is fractured and cranial nerve VII is affected?","explanation":"The **stapedius muscle** is a small muscle located in the middle ear. It arises from the posterior wall of the tympanic cavity and inserts onto the neck of the stapes bone. The primary function of the stapedius muscle is to dampen excessive vibrations of the stapes bone, which helps protect the delicate structures of the inner ear from loud sounds. \r\n\r\nThe facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) provides innervation to the stapedius muscle. Damage to the facial nerve can result in weakness or paralysis of the stapedius muscle, leading to a loss of its protective function. This can result in symptoms such as hyperacusis (increased sensitivity to loud sounds) and a reduced ability to tolerate loud noises.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 931, 981.","responses":[{"text":"Temporalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stapedius","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral pterygoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Masseter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tensor tympani","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11803,"text":"Nasolacrimal duct drains tears to which of the following parts of the nose?","explanation":"Tears are produced by the lacrimal glands and help keep the surface of the eyes moist and protected. Excess tears and fluid drain through the lacrimal puncta, which are small openings located at the inner corner of the eye. From there, tears flow into the lacrimal canaliculi and then into the lacrimal sac. Finally, the nasolacrimal duct connects the lacrimal sac to the **inferior nasal meatus**, which is located in the nasal cavity.\r\n\r\nBy draining into the inferior nasal meatus, tears are able to mix with the nasal secretions and eventually reach the back of the throat, without causing excessive watering or overflow of tears.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 901.","responses":[{"text":"Lacrimal sac","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior nasal conchae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior nasal meatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle nasal meatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior nasal meatus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11804,"text":"Which of the following is responsible for the detection of the direction from which the sound is coming?","explanation":"The **lateral superior olivary nucleus** (LSO) receives input from both ears and plays a crucial role in comparing the intensity and timing differences of sound signals arriving at each ear. It acts as a binaural processing center, allowing for the localization of sound sources in space. Neurons in the LSO are sensitive to differences in sound arrival time and sound intensity between the ears.\r\n\r\nThe medial geniculate body is involved in relaying auditory information to the auditory cortex, while the trapezoid body is responsible for transmitting sound localization cues from the cochlear nuclei to the superior olivary nuclei. The red nucleus and the lateral geniculate body are not directly involved in sound localization.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 937.","responses":[{"text":"Lateral geniculate body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial geniculate body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trapezoid body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral superior olivary nucleus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11805,"text":"Parasympathetic fibers arising from which of the following are responsible for the constriction of a pupil and making a lens more convex?","explanation":"The **constriction of the pupil (miosis)** and the **accommodation of the lens for near vision (accommodation)** are controlled by the parasympathetic fibers of the autonomic nervous system. These fibers arise from the **ciliary ganglion**.\r\n\r\nThe parasympathetic fibers responsible for pupillary constriction originate from the **Edinger-Westphal nucleus** in the midbrain. They travel with the **oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III)** and synapse at the ciliary ganglion. From there, postganglionic fibers innervate the **sphincter pupillae muscle** of the iris, causing pupillary constriction.\r\n\r\nSimilarly, the parasympathetic fibers responsible for lens accommodation also originate from the Edinger-Westphal nucleus and pass through the ciliary ganglion. They innervate the **ciliary muscle**, which contracts to increase the curvature of the lens, allowing for near vision.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 1066.","responses":[{"text":"Ciliary ganglion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Otic ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterygopalatine ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior cervical ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11806,"text":"Nucleus ambigous does not give fibers to which of the following?","explanation":"The **nucleus ambiguus** is a motor nucleus located in the medulla oblongata. It supplies motor innervation to several muscles involved in swallowing and phonation. It gives fibers to the intrinsic muscles of the larynx, which are important for controlling vocal cord movement during speech and swallowing. The nucleus ambiguus also supplies the nerve to stylopharyngeus, which innervates the stylopharyngeus muscle involved in pharyngeal constriction during swallowing.\r\n\r\nHowever, the **tensor veli palatini** muscle, which is responsible for tensing the soft palate, receives its motor innervation from a different source. It is innervated by the **mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve** (V3). The tensor veli palatini muscle functions to open the auditory tube during swallowing and yawning.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 1067.","responses":[{"text":"Nerve to stylopharyngeus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Constrictor muscles of pharynx","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior two-thirds of esophagus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tensor veli palatini","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrinsic muscles of larynx","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11807,"text":"A person comes to the clinic with complaints of drooping of the right upper eyelid and inability to keep his right eye open. Which of the following muscles is most likely involved?","explanation":"The **levator palpebrae superioris** is the primary muscle responsible for raising the upper eyelid. It is innervated by the oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III). When this muscle is affected, it can result in a condition called **ptosis**, characterized by drooping of the eyelid.\r\n\r\nPtosis can occur due to various reasons, including dysfunction or weakness of the levator palpebrae superioris muscle or its innervation. In this case, the presentation suggests involvement of the right levator palpebrae superioris, leading to the inability to keep the right eye open.\r\n\r\nThe orbicularis oculi muscle is responsible for closing the eyelids, while the superior rectus, superior oblique, and inferior oblique muscles are primarily involved in eye movement. Therefore, their dysfunction would not typically lead to drooping of the eyelid.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 908.","responses":[{"text":"Orbicularis oculi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior oblique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior rectus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior oblique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Levator palpebrae superioris","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11808,"text":"Which of the following are found abundantly in the fovea?","explanation":"The structures that are abundantly found in the **fovea**, a small depression in the retina responsible for high acuity vision, are **cones**.\r\n\r\nThe fovea is a specialized region located in the center of the macula, which is the central part of the retina. It contains a high density of cone cells, which are photoreceptor cells responsible for color vision and visual acuity. Cones are concentrated in the fovea to maximize visual resolution and enable detailed vision.\r\n\r\nUnlike rods, which are more abundant in the peripheral regions of the retina and are responsible for low-light and peripheral vision, cones are specialized for bright light conditions and provide high-resolution color vision. The concentration of cones in the fovea allows for precise focusing of light onto the central part of the retina, leading to the sharpest and clearest vision.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 640.","responses":[{"text":"Bipolar cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cones","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rods","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxyntic cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endothelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11809,"text":"A few students while conducting research found that some areas of the tongue are stimulated when they get in touch with ionized molecules. Which of the following taste sensations will be produced by these ionized molecules?","explanation":"The sense of taste, or gustation, is mediated by taste buds located on the surface of the tongue. Taste buds contain specialized taste receptor cells that detect different taste sensations. These taste receptor cells are sensitive to specific molecules present in the food or drink.\r\n\r\nThe taste sensation of **salty** is primarily detected by taste receptor cells that are responsive to ionized molecules, such as sodium (Na+) and potassium (K+). When these ionized molecules come in contact with the taste buds, they trigger a neural signal that is interpreted by the brain as a salty taste.\r\n\r\nSimilarly, the taste sensation of **sour** is also produced by ionized molecules, specifically hydrogen ions (H+). Sour taste receptor cells respond to the acidity of substances, such as citric acid or vinegar, and transmit the signal of sourness to the brain.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 675.","responses":[{"text":"Salty and umami","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salty and sweet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bitter and sweet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sweet and umami","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salty and sour","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11810,"text":"Which of the following is a voluntary phase of swallowing?","explanation":"**Swallowing** is a coordinated process involving multiple phases. The **oral phase** is the initial voluntary phase of swallowing, where food or liquid is moved from the mouth to the pharynx. During this phase, the tongue pushes the food or liquid to the back of the mouth, initiating the swallowing reflex.\r\n\r\nThe subsequent phases of swallowing, such as the pharyngeal phase and esophageal phase, are involuntary and occur automatically. The pharyngeal phase involves the closure of the nasal passages and elevation of the larynx to prevent food from entering the airway. The esophageal phase involves the peristaltic contractions of the esophagus to propel the food towards the stomach.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 797.","responses":[{"text":"Intestinal phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saliva secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral phase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pharyngeal phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal phase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11811,"text":"Which of the following is the most important process in swallowing that prevents the entry of food into the larynx?","explanation":"During swallowing, the **larynx is elevated and moves forward**, causing the epiglottis to fold downward and cover the opening of the larynx. This movement helps to prevent food and liquids from entering the airway and directs them towards the esophagus. The elevation and forward movement of the larynx are coordinated by the action of various muscles, including the suprahyoid and infrahyoid muscles.\r\n\r\nThe closure of the **epiglottis** is also an important step in swallowing to protect the airway. However, the forward movement of the larynx is considered the most crucial process in preventing the entry of food into the larynx.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 798.","responses":[{"text":"Upward movement of uvula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Closure of vocal cords","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Forward movement of larynx","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Upward movement of pharynx","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opening of epiglottis","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

export default a